WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

2
00:02:05.872 --> 00:02:08.024
LEWIS ON RADIO: All right. team.
stay in sight of each other.

3
00:02:08.124 --> 00:02:10.484
Let's make NASA proud today.

4
00:02:10.584 --> 00:02:12.194
MARTINEZ:
How's it looking over there. Watney?

5
00:02:12.294 --> 00:02:16.616
WATNEY: Well. you'll be happy to hear
that in Grid Section 14-28.

6
00:02:16.716 --> 00:02:19.584
the particles were predominantly coarse.

7
00:02:19.684 --> 00:02:22.894
but in 29. they're... they're much finer

8
00:02:22.994 --> 00:02:24.958
and they should be ideal
for chem analysis.

9
00:02:25.058 --> 00:02:27.895
MARTINEZ: Oh. wow. Did everybody
hear that? Mark just discovered dirt.

10
00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:29.546
(LAUGHS) Should we alert the media?

11
00:02:29.646 --> 00:02:33.551
Sorry. what are you doing today. Martinez?
Making sure the MAV is still upright?

12
00:02:33.651 --> 00:02:35.845
MARTINEZ: I'd like you to know
that visual inspection of the equipment

13
00:02:35.945 --> 00:02:37.530
is imperative to mission success.

14
00:02:37.655 --> 00:02:40.541
I also would like to report
that the MAV is still upright.

15
00:02:40.641 --> 00:02:43.036
LEWIS: (SIGHS) Watney.
you keep leaving your channel open

16
00:02:43.161 --> 00:02:45.004
which leads to Martinez responding

17
00:02:45.104 --> 00:02:48.200
which leads to all of us listening
which leads to me being annoyed.

18
00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:50.928
WATNEY: Roger that. Martinez.
the captain would like you to please...

19
00:02:51.028 --> 00:02:53.630
- shut your smart mouth.
- (LAUGHING)

20
00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:57.117
We'd prefer to use a different adjective
to describe Martinez's mouth.

21
00:02:57.217 --> 00:03:01.055
- MARTINEZ: Oh. did Beck just insult me?
- WATNEY: "Dr. Beck." And yes.

22
00:03:01.155 --> 00:03:04.843
Happy to turn the radios off from here.
Commander. Just say the word.

23
00:03:04.943 --> 00:03:07.703
Wait. Johanssen. Constant
communication is the hallmark...

24
00:03:07.804 --> 00:03:09.831
- Shut 'em off.
- WATNEY: No.

25
00:03:09.931 --> 00:03:11.992
No. Excuse me.

26
00:03:12.092 --> 00:03:14.152
LEWIS:
I apologize for my countrymen. Vogel.

27
00:03:14.252 --> 00:03:17.856
VOGEL: Accepted. How many samples
do we need. Commander?

28
00:03:17.956 --> 00:03:21.227
LEWIS: Seven. 100 grams each.

29
00:03:22.328 --> 00:03:25.348
(ALARM BLARING)

30
00:03:26.473 --> 00:03:29.035
We have a mission update.
A storm warning.

31
00:03:29.135 --> 00:03:31.971
Commander. you should come inside.
You're gonna want to see this.

32
00:03:32.071 --> 00:03:34.173
- What is it?
- JOHANSSEN: A storm warning.

33
00:03:34.273 --> 00:03:37.820
LEWIS: I saw that in this morning's briefing.
We'll be inside before it hits.

34
00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:40.881
Yeah. they upgraded their estimate.

35
00:03:40.981 --> 00:03:43.826
The storm's gonna be a lot worse.

36
00:03:49.014 --> 00:03:52.060
LEWIS: Martinez. how does it look?

37
00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:53.912
MARTINEZ: Not good.

38
00:03:55.171 --> 00:03:59.183
"1.200 kilometers in diameter.
bearing 24.41 degrees."

39
00:03:59.283 --> 00:04:00.401
That's tracking right towards us.

40
00:04:00.501 --> 00:04:05.298
"Based on current escalation.
estimated force of 8.600 newtons."

41
00:04:05.398 --> 00:04:08.936
- What's the abort force?
- 7.500.

42
00:04:09.436 --> 00:04:11.671
MARTINEZ: Anything more than that
and the MAV could tip.

43
00:04:11.771 --> 00:04:14.984
- Do we scrub?
- Begin abort procedure.

44
00:04:15.084 --> 00:04:19.313
VOGEL: We are estimating with a margin
of error. We... could wait it out.

45
00:04:19.413 --> 00:04:21.564
WATNEY: Let's wait it out.

46
00:04:22.416 --> 00:04:24.736
Let's wait it out.

47
00:04:25.395 --> 00:04:29.265
- JOHANSSEN: Commander?
- Prep emergency departure.

48
00:04:29.365 --> 00:04:32.164
- WATNEY: Commander?
- LEWIS: We're scrubbed. That's an order.

49
00:04:42.839 --> 00:04:46.508
- Martinez. how long before take-off?
- 12 minutes.

50
00:04:46.608 --> 00:04:48.579
(ALARM BLARING)

51
00:04:49.862 --> 00:04:54.033
LEWIS: Visibility is almost zero. Anyone
gets lost. hone in on my suit's telemetry.

52
00:04:54.133 --> 00:04:56.998
- You ready?
- Ready.

53
00:04:57.687 --> 00:04:58.763
(ALL GROAN)

54
00:04:58.864 --> 00:05:02.528
- WATNEY: Commander. are you okay?
- I'm okay.

55
00:05:04.127 --> 00:05:06.153
(WIND HOWLING)

56
00:05:11.284 --> 00:05:12.912
(STRAINING)

57
00:05:13.412 --> 00:05:15.422
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

58
00:05:25.708 --> 00:05:28.879
Commander. we're at 10 degrees.
and the MAV is gonna tip at 12.3.

59
00:05:29.379 --> 00:05:32.842
WATNEY: Hey! We might be able
to keep the MAV from tipping.

60
00:05:32.942 --> 00:05:34.051
How?

61
00:05:34.151 --> 00:05:37.171
Use the cables from the comms
mast as guy-lines.

62
00:05:37.271 --> 00:05:40.549
- anchor it with the Rover's.
- LEWIS: Watch out!

63
00:05:40.649 --> 00:05:41.758
(WATNEY GROANS)

64
00:05:41.859 --> 00:05:43.527
(SCREAMING)

65
00:05:43.627 --> 00:05:45.450
Watney!

66
00:05:46.389 --> 00:05:48.783
FEMALE AUTOMATED VOICE:
Warning. Suit breach detected.

67
00:05:48.884 --> 00:05:50.510
- What happened?
- He was hit.

68
00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:51.853
Watney. report.

69
00:05:51.953 --> 00:05:54.764
Before we lost telemetry.
his decompression alarm went off.

70
00:05:54.865 --> 00:05:57.358
- LEWIS: Where did you last see him?
- I don't know where he is.

71
00:05:57.458 --> 00:05:59.485
- LEWIS: What are the vitals on his suit?
- He's offline.

72
00:05:59.585 --> 00:06:00.987
BECK:
A complete loss of signal on Watney.

73
00:06:01.087 --> 00:06:02.223
- VOGEL: Beck!
- Yeah.

74
00:06:02.323 --> 00:06:06.180
- How long can he survive decompression?
- Less than a minute.

75
00:06:06.427 --> 00:06:08.758
Line up. walk west.

76
00:06:08.859 --> 00:06:11.816
He may be prone.
We don't wanna step over him.

77
00:06:12.616 --> 00:06:16.498
- MARTINEZ: Commander We're at 10.5 degrees.
- AUTOMATED VOICE: Warning. Excessive tilt.

78
00:06:16.598 --> 00:06:19.843
Tilting to 11 with all
the gusts of wind.

79
00:06:19.943 --> 00:06:23.520
Copy that. Everyone.
hone in on Martinez's suit.

80
00:06:23.620 --> 00:06:26.148
It'll get you to airlock.
Get in. prep for launch.

81
00:06:26.248 --> 00:06:29.784
- BECK: What about you. Commander?
- I'm gonna search a little longer.

82
00:06:29.885 --> 00:06:33.119
Get moving! Go!

83
00:06:35.624 --> 00:06:38.995
Watney! Watney. report!

84
00:06:39.095 --> 00:06:43.122
MARTINEZ: The MAV's at 11.6 degrees.
One good gust and we're tipping.

85
00:06:43.222 --> 00:06:46.269
- If it tips. you launch.
- You really think I'm gonna leave you behind?

86
00:06:46.369 --> 00:06:50.657
- LEWIS: That's an order. Martinez. Mark!
- (BECK GRUNTING)

87
00:06:50.757 --> 00:06:54.006
Mark! Can you hear me?

88
00:06:55.279 --> 00:06:59.691
Martinez. what about the proximity radar?
Could that detect Watney's suit?

89
00:06:59.791 --> 00:07:03.528
It's made to see the Hermes from orbit not
a little piece of metal from a single suit.

90
00:07:03.628 --> 00:07:05.189
- LEWIS: Give it a try.
- MARTINEZ: Roger.

91
00:07:05.289 --> 00:07:08.309
VOGEL: What is she thinking? She knows
the infrared can't get through a sandstorm.

92
00:07:08.409 --> 00:07:10.403
BECK: She's grasping for anything.

93
00:07:10.503 --> 00:07:12.772
MARTINEZ: We've got negative contact
on the proximity radar.

94
00:07:12.873 --> 00:07:15.996
- LEWIS: Nothing?
- MARTINEZ: No. I can barely see the Hab.

95
00:07:16.676 --> 00:07:20.505
Commander. I know you don't
wanna hear this. but... Mark is dead.

96
00:07:22.007 --> 00:07:23.417
Commander!

97
00:07:23.517 --> 00:07:25.978
Hey. what the hell
is wrong with you. man?

98
00:07:26.078 --> 00:07:28.464
My friend just died.
I don't want my commander to die. too.

99
00:07:28.564 --> 00:07:31.000
- AUTOMATED VOICE: Stability warning.
- We're tipping!

100
00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:34.461
BECK: Commander. you need
to get back to the ship. now!

101
00:07:35.062 --> 00:07:36.050
13 degrees.

102
00:07:36.150 --> 00:07:38.040
If we pass balance.
we'll never rock back.

103
00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:41.095
MARTINEZ: I've got one more trick left.
and then I'm following orders. Commander.

104
00:07:43.104 --> 00:07:45.129
- You're firing the OMS?
- (ALARM BEEPING)

105
00:07:45.229 --> 00:07:47.256
That's right.

106
00:07:50.037 --> 00:07:53.887
- Commander!
- LEWIS: On my way. (BREATHING HEAVILY)

107
00:07:56.419 --> 00:07:58.659
- MARTINEZ: Johanssen. let's go.
- (SIGHS)

108
00:08:01.132 --> 00:08:03.168
(STRUGGLING)

109
00:08:05.236 --> 00:08:07.217
LEWIS: Mark!

110
00:08:19.584 --> 00:08:22.619
MARTINEZ: We're at 11.5 and holding.

111
00:08:24.573 --> 00:08:27.070
Ready to go on your command.

112
00:08:28.301 --> 00:08:30.388
Ready to launch.

113
00:08:30.488 --> 00:08:33.872
Commander. I need you to verbally
tell me whether or not to.

114
00:08:33.972 --> 00:08:35.846
Launch.

115
00:09:16.529 --> 00:09:19.598
SANDERS ON TV: At around 4:30 a.m.
Central Standard Time

116
00:09:19.698 --> 00:09:24.838
our satellites detected a storm approaching
the Ares 3 mission site on Mars.

117
00:09:24.938 --> 00:09:28.117
At 6:45. the storm
had escalated to severe

118
00:09:28.217 --> 00:09:31.327
and we had no choice
but to abort the mission.

119
00:09:31.427 --> 00:09:34.056
Thanks to the quick action
of Commander Lewis

120
00:09:34.156 --> 00:09:37.381
astronauts Beck. Johanssen.
Martinez and Vogel

121
00:09:37.481 --> 00:09:40.137
were all able to reach
the Mars Ascent Vehicle

122
00:09:40.237 --> 00:09:45.334
and perform an emergency launch
at 7:28 Central Time.

123
00:09:45.434 --> 00:09:47.694
Unfortunately. during the evacuation.

124
00:09:47.794 --> 00:09:51.774
astronaut Mark Watney
was struck by debris and killed.

125
00:09:51.875 --> 00:09:53.126
- (REPORTERS GASP)
- (CAMERAS CLICKING)

126
00:09:53.226 --> 00:09:56.780
Commander Lewis and the rest of her team
were able to intercept safely

127
00:09:56.881 --> 00:09:59.615
with the Hermes
and are now heading home.

128
00:09:59.715 --> 00:10:02.493
But Mark Watney is dead.

129
00:10:02.593 --> 00:10:05.074
- FEMALE REPORTER: Director Sanders!
- (REPORTERS CLAMORING)

130
00:10:07.373 --> 00:10:08.494
Director Sanders!

131
00:10:27.066 --> 00:10:29.081
(DEVICE BEEPING)

132
00:10:36.754 --> 00:10:38.232
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

133
00:10:38.432 --> 00:10:41.587
AUTOMATED VOICE: Oxygen level critical.

134
00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:50.187
Oxygen level critical.

135
00:10:53.648 --> 00:10:55.742
(BEEPING CONTINUES)

136
00:10:56.043 --> 00:10:58.703
- Oxygen level cri...
- (BEEPING STOPS)

137
00:11:00.647 --> 00:11:02.469
(GROANING)

138
00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:12.106
(YELPS)

139
00:11:12.206 --> 00:11:14.449
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

140
00:11:22.428 --> 00:11:24.356
(GROANING)

141
00:11:51.418 --> 00:11:53.472
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

142
00:12:05.591 --> 00:12:08.323
- (DOOR BEEPING)
- (BUZZING)

143
00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:18.523
AUTOMATED VOICE: Pressure stable.

144
00:12:50.564 --> 00:12:52.174
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

145
00:12:53.976 --> 00:12:55.534
(SCREAMING IN PAIN)

146
00:13:55.834 --> 00:13:57.888
(GRUNTS)

147
00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:16.118
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

148
00:14:19.992 --> 00:14:22.005
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

149
00:14:54.863 --> 00:14:56.955
(GROANING)

150
00:15:00.535 --> 00:15:02.587
(STAPLER CLATTERS)

151
00:15:03.288 --> 00:15:05.336
(GROANS)

152
00:15:05.875 --> 00:15:07.812
(EXHALING DEEPLY)

153
00:15:18.054 --> 00:15:19.092
Fuck.

154
00:15:49.104 --> 00:15:50.197
Okay.

155
00:15:50.297 --> 00:15:52.095
Okay.

156
00:15:53.316 --> 00:15:57.622
Hello. this is Mark Watney. astronaut.

157
00:15:58.113 --> 00:16:01.241
I'm entering this log for the record...

158
00:16:01.341 --> 00:16:03.917
in case I don't make it.

159
00:16:04.273 --> 00:16:06.234
It is...

160
00:16:06.534 --> 00:16:08.967
06:53...

161
00:16:09.067 --> 00:16:12.378
on Sol 19 and...

162
00:16:12.478 --> 00:16:14.713
I'm alive.

163
00:16:14.814 --> 00:16:17.026
Obviously. But...

164
00:16:17.126 --> 00:16:22.164
I'm guessing that's gonna come as a surprise
to my crewmates and to NASA.

165
00:16:22.264 --> 00:16:25.938
And to the entire world. really. so...

166
00:16:28.070 --> 00:16:30.232
Surprise.

167
00:16:30.873 --> 00:16:33.150
I did not die on Sol 18.

168
00:16:33.250 --> 00:16:35.078
Best I can figure...

169
00:16:35.178 --> 00:16:38.990
this length of our primary communications
antenna broke off...

170
00:16:39.090 --> 00:16:44.170
and tore through my bio-monitor
and ripped a hole in me as well.

171
00:16:44.495 --> 00:16:47.582
But the antenna and the blood. really.

172
00:16:47.682 --> 00:16:51.303
managed to seal the breach in my suit
which kept me alive.

173
00:16:51.403 --> 00:16:54.473
even though the crew
must have thought I was dead.

174
00:16:54.573 --> 00:16:57.184
I have no way to contact NASA.

175
00:16:57.284 --> 00:16:59.450
And even if I could. it's gonna be...

176
00:16:59.550 --> 00:17:03.385
four years until a manned
mission can reach me.

177
00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:06.027
And I'm in a Hab designed
to last 31 days.

178
00:17:06.127 --> 00:17:08.405
If the oxygenator breaks.
I'm gonna suffocate.

179
00:17:08.505 --> 00:17:10.874
If the water reclaimer breaks.
I'll die of thirst.

180
00:17:10.974 --> 00:17:15.320
If the Hab breaches.
I'm just gonna. kind of implode.

181
00:17:15.821 --> 00:17:19.207
And if by some miracle.
none of that happens...

182
00:17:19.307 --> 00:17:22.035
eventually I'm gonna run out of food.

183
00:17:23.171 --> 00:17:25.014
So...

184
00:17:25.915 --> 00:17:27.795
yeah.

185
00:17:30.644 --> 00:17:32.513
Yeah.

186
00:17:35.108 --> 00:17:37.226
(CLEARS THROAT)

187
00:17:37.526 --> 00:17:39.279
(SIGHS)

188
00:17:46.586 --> 00:17:48.777
(COMPUTER BEEPING)

189
00:19:20.686 --> 00:19:23.141
I'm not gonna die here.

190
00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:05.268
32...

191
00:20:05.368 --> 00:20:07.386
33...

192
00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:11.077
34...

193
00:20:11.177 --> 00:20:12.992
35. 36.

194
00:20:13.092 --> 00:20:15.769
Sweet and sour chicken.

195
00:20:15.870 --> 00:20:17.898
(GROANS SOFTLY)

196
00:20:30.085 --> 00:20:32.081
(FLUSHING)

197
00:20:32.181 --> 00:20:34.227
(WHIRRING)

198
00:20:48.146 --> 00:20:50.182
What do we got?

199
00:20:52.117 --> 00:20:54.211
(TYPING)

200
00:20:56.113 --> 00:20:58.590
Right. let's do the math.

201
00:20:58.690 --> 00:21:02.344
Our surface mission here
was supposed to last 31 sols.

202
00:21:02.444 --> 00:21:05.614
For redundancy. they sent 68 sols
worth of food. That's for 6 people.

203
00:21:05.714 --> 00:21:08.392
So for just me.
that's gonna last 300 sols

204
00:21:08.492 --> 00:21:11.822
which I figure I can stretch
to 400 if I ration. So...

205
00:21:11.922 --> 00:21:14.992
I got to figure out a way to grow

206
00:21:15.092 --> 00:21:17.519
three years' worth of food here.

207
00:21:17.619 --> 00:21:20.372
On a planet where nothing grows.

208
00:21:20.672 --> 00:21:22.524
Luckily...

209
00:21:24.609 --> 00:21:26.996
I'm a botanist.

210
00:21:29.490 --> 00:21:34.359
Mars will come to fear my botany powers.

211
00:21:55.100 --> 00:21:56.487
(STRAINING)

212
00:22:19.168 --> 00:22:21.837
AUTOMATED VOICE: Pressure stable.

213
00:22:31.298 --> 00:22:33.888
Staple came out.

214
00:22:43.026 --> 00:22:45.064
(PANTING)

215
00:23:22.568 --> 00:23:24.449
Fuck you. Mars.

216
00:23:39.821 --> 00:23:42.367
Johanssen. Jesus.

217
00:23:49.005 --> 00:23:50.012
(GAGS)

218
00:24:31.383 --> 00:24:33.643
MEN: <i>...Monday. Happy Days</i>

219
00:24:33.743 --> 00:24:36.106
<i>Tuesday. Wednesday. Happy Days</i>

220
00:24:36.206 --> 00:24:38.548
<i>Thursday. Friday. Happy Days</i>

221
00:24:38.648 --> 00:24:41.169
<i>The weekend comes. my cycle hums</i>

222
00:24:41.269 --> 00:24:43.138
<i>Ready to race to you</i>

223
00:24:43.238 --> 00:24:45.498
WATNEY: The problem is water.

224
00:24:45.999 --> 00:24:51.169
I have created
126 square meters of soil.

225
00:24:51.269 --> 00:24:56.398
But every cubic meter of soil requires
40 liters of water to be farmable.

226
00:24:56.598 --> 00:25:00.004
So I gotta make a lot more water.

227
00:25:00.731 --> 00:25:05.271
Good thing is. I know the recipe. You take
hydrogen. you add oxygen. you burn.

228
00:25:05.837 --> 00:25:11.203
Now. I have hundreds of liters
of unused hydrazine at the MDV.

229
00:25:11.603 --> 00:25:14.554
If I run the hydrazine
over an iridium catalyst.

230
00:25:14.654 --> 00:25:17.132
it'll separate into N2 and H2.

231
00:25:17.232 --> 00:25:21.203
And then if I just direct
the hydrogen into a small area...

232
00:25:21.703 --> 00:25:23.380
and burn it.

233
00:25:23.981 --> 00:25:26.766
Luckily. in the history of humanity

234
00:25:26.867 --> 00:25:32.301
nothing bad has ever happened
from lighting hydrogen on fire.

235
00:25:32.401 --> 00:25:34.183
NASA hates fire.

236
00:25:34.283 --> 00:25:38.429
Because of the whole "fire makes
everybody die in space" thing.

237
00:25:38.529 --> 00:25:41.349
So. everything they sent us
up here with is flame-retardant

238
00:25:41.449 --> 00:25:45.733
with the notable exception of...

239
00:25:46.346 --> 00:25:49.183
Martinez's personal items.

240
00:25:49.283 --> 00:25:51.969
I am sorry. Martinez. but if you didn't
want me to go through your stuff

241
00:25:52.069 --> 00:25:54.930
you shouldn't have left me
for dead on a desolate planet.

242
00:25:55.630 --> 00:25:59.451
By the way. I'm figuring you're gonna be
fine with this. given my present situation.

243
00:25:59.551 --> 00:26:01.370
(THE FONZ ON TV. INDISTINCT)

244
00:26:01.821 --> 00:26:03.341
Counting on you.

245
00:26:05.075 --> 00:26:07.141
(BLOWING)

246
00:26:19.398 --> 00:26:21.175
(SIZZLING)

247
00:26:23.911 --> 00:26:25.799
Whoo!

248
00:26:28.224 --> 00:26:30.321
- (GROANS)
- (EARS RINGING)

249
00:26:37.059 --> 00:26:40.345
So. yeah. I blew myself up.

250
00:26:40.645 --> 00:26:43.031
Best guess...

251
00:26:43.131 --> 00:26:45.689
I forgot to...

252
00:26:45.789 --> 00:26:49.175
account for the excess oxygen that...

253
00:26:49.529 --> 00:26:53.467
I've been exhaling
when I did my calculations.

254
00:26:53.567 --> 00:26:55.741
Because I'm stupid.

255
00:26:58.264 --> 00:27:00.533
Yeah. I'm gonna get back to work here.

256
00:27:00.633 --> 00:27:03.647
just as soon as my ears stop ringing.

257
00:27:08.008 --> 00:27:12.337
Interesting side note. this is actually
how the Jet Propulsion Lab was founded.

258
00:27:12.437 --> 00:27:15.825
Five guys at Caltech
were trying to make rocket fuel

259
00:27:15.925 --> 00:27:17.784
and they nearly burned down their dorm.

260
00:27:17.885 --> 00:27:22.006
And rather than expel them
they banished them to a nearby farm.

261
00:27:22.106 --> 00:27:24.450
told them to keep working.

262
00:27:24.550 --> 00:27:27.312
- And now we have a space program.
- (GASPS)

263
00:27:29.797 --> 00:27:31.571
Okay.

264
00:27:34.785 --> 00:27:36.864
(SNORING)

265
00:28:48.323 --> 00:28:49.941
Hey. there.

266
00:28:59.968 --> 00:29:03.580
SANDERS: The nation was blessed
to have Mark serving in our space program.

267
00:29:03.680 --> 00:29:06.012
While his loss will be deeply felt.

268
00:29:06.112 --> 00:29:08.685
the men and women of NASA
will soldier forth

269
00:29:08.785 --> 00:29:12.089
onward and upward
in the mission of their agency.

270
00:29:12.189 --> 00:29:16.644
By doing so. they honor the legacy.
Mark's leaving behind.

271
00:29:16.744 --> 00:29:20.773
and they ensure his sacrifice
will not be in vain.

272
00:29:31.201 --> 00:29:34.597
I have the honor of speaking not only
for the men and women of NASA

273
00:29:34.697 --> 00:29:36.349
but for people all over the world...

274
00:29:36.449 --> 00:29:39.649
VINCENT: I thought you gave
a lovely speech. by the way.

275
00:29:40.261 --> 00:29:41.537
(TURNS OFF TV)

276
00:29:41.637 --> 00:29:45.103
- I need you to authorize my satellite time.
- It's not gonna happen.

277
00:29:45.203 --> 00:29:46.943
We're funded for five Ares missions.

278
00:29:47.043 --> 00:29:49.338
I think I can get Congress
to authorize a sixth.

279
00:29:49.438 --> 00:29:51.581
- No.
- Ares 3 evac'd after 18 sols.

280
00:29:51.681 --> 00:29:53.926
There's half a mission worth
of supplies up there.

281
00:29:54.026 --> 00:29:56.503
I can sell it at a fraction
of the cost of a normal mission

282
00:29:56.603 --> 00:29:58.622
and all I have to know is
what's left of our assets.

283
00:29:58.722 --> 00:30:00.532
You're not the only one
who needs satellite time.

284
00:30:00.632 --> 00:30:02.769
We've got the Ares 4
supply missions coming up.

285
00:30:02.870 --> 00:30:05.104
We should be focusing
on the Schiaparelli Crater.

286
00:30:05.204 --> 00:30:07.265
We got 12 satellites up there.
We can spare a few hours...

287
00:30:07.365 --> 00:30:11.318
It's not about the satellite time. Vince.
We're a public domain organization.

288
00:30:11.418 --> 00:30:13.246
- We need to be transparent on this.
- Okay.

289
00:30:13.346 --> 00:30:16.224
The second we point the satellites
at the Hab I broadcast pictures

290
00:30:16.324 --> 00:30:19.710
- of Mark Watney's dead body to the world.
- You're afraid of a PR problem?

291
00:30:19.811 --> 00:30:22.882
Of course I'm afraid of a PR problem.
Another mission?

292
00:30:22.982 --> 00:30:25.409
Congress won't reimburse us
for a paper clip

293
00:30:25.509 --> 00:30:28.520
if I put a dead astronaut on the front
page of The Washington Post.

294
00:30:28.620 --> 00:30:31.740
He's not going anywhere. Teddy.
I mean. he's not...

295
00:30:31.841 --> 00:30:35.102
He's not gonna decompose. you know.
He's gonna be up there forever.

296
00:30:35.202 --> 00:30:37.981
Meteorology estimates
that he'll be covered in sand

297
00:30:38.081 --> 00:30:39.799
from normal weather activity
within a year.

298
00:30:39.900 --> 00:30:41.759
We can't wait a year. We got work to do.

299
00:30:41.860 --> 00:30:45.597
Ares 5 won't even launch for five years.
We have plenty of time.

300
00:30:45.697 --> 00:30:47.532
Okay.

301
00:30:47.833 --> 00:30:49.692
Okay.

302
00:30:50.193 --> 00:30:52.905
Okay. consider this. (CLEARS THROAT)

303
00:30:53.005 --> 00:30:56.400
Right now. the world's on our side.

304
00:30:56.500 --> 00:31:00.822
Sympathy for the Watney family.
Ares 6 could bring his body home.

305
00:31:00.922 --> 00:31:03.599
Now... we don't say
that's the purpose of the mission

306
00:31:03.699 --> 00:31:06.794
but we make it clear that that would be
a part of it. We frame it that way.

307
00:31:07.295 --> 00:31:11.383
More support from Congress.
But not if we wait a year.

308
00:31:11.483 --> 00:31:14.161
- We wait a year. nobody gives a shit.
- (MICROWAVE TIMER DINGS)

309
00:31:23.703 --> 00:31:25.805
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

310
00:31:37.760 --> 00:31:39.833
(COMPUTER CHIMES)

311
00:31:45.895 --> 00:31:47.914
Vincent Kapoor?

312
00:31:53.335 --> 00:31:54.877
6-2.

313
00:31:56.038 --> 00:31:58.358
7-6-2.

314
00:32:01.053 --> 00:32:03.457
Acidalia Planitia.

315
00:32:14.707 --> 00:32:16.387
What?

316
00:32:30.892 --> 00:32:33.854
Hi. Security?
This is Mindy Park in SatCon.

317
00:32:33.954 --> 00:32:37.191
I need the emergency contact
for Vincent Kapoor.

318
00:32:37.291 --> 00:32:40.644
Yes. him. Yes. it's an emergency!

319
00:32:46.158 --> 00:32:49.270
- SANDERS: How sure?
- 100%.

320
00:32:49.370 --> 00:32:51.848
You've got to be shitting me.

321
00:32:51.948 --> 00:32:53.591
SANDERS: Prove it to me.

322
00:32:55.443 --> 00:32:57.653
For a start...

323
00:32:57.954 --> 00:33:01.958
- the solar panels have been cleaned.
- They could have been cleaned by wind.

324
00:33:02.058 --> 00:33:04.503
Back it up. Look at Rover 2.

325
00:33:04.603 --> 00:33:07.139
According to the logs.
Commander Lewis took it out on Sol 17

326
00:33:07.239 --> 00:33:10.952
plugged it into the Hab to recharge.
It's been moved.

327
00:33:11.052 --> 00:33:14.263
- She could have forgotten to log the move.
- No. not likely.

328
00:33:14.363 --> 00:33:17.633
Why don't we just ask Lewis? Let's get
on CAPCOM and ask her directly right now.

329
00:33:17.733 --> 00:33:21.897
No. No. If Watney is really alive.
we don't want the Ares 3 crew to know.

330
00:33:21.997 --> 00:33:23.523
How can you not tell them?

331
00:33:23.623 --> 00:33:26.885
They have another 10 months on their
trip home. Space travel is dangerous.

332
00:33:26.985 --> 00:33:29.813
- They need to be alert and undistracted.
- But they already think he's dead.

333
00:33:29.913 --> 00:33:32.925
And they'd be devastated to find out
they left him there alive.

334
00:33:33.325 --> 00:33:37.957
I'm sorry. but you have not thought this
through. I mean. what are we gonna say?

335
00:33:38.057 --> 00:33:41.943
"Dear America. remember that astronaut
we killed and had a really nice funeral for?

336
00:33:42.043 --> 00:33:46.272
"Turns out he's alive and we left him
on Mars. Our bad. Sincerely. NASA."

337
00:33:46.372 --> 00:33:49.358
I mean. do you realize the shitstorm
that is about to hit us?

338
00:33:49.458 --> 00:33:51.936
How are we going to handle the public?

339
00:33:52.036 --> 00:33:54.706
Legally. we have 24 hours
to release these pictures.

340
00:33:54.807 --> 00:33:58.560
We release a statement with them. We don't
want people working it out on their own.

341
00:33:58.961 --> 00:34:01.038
- Yes. sir.
- But if my math is right.

342
00:34:01.138 --> 00:34:04.822
he's going to starve to death
long before we can help him.

343
00:34:06.635 --> 00:34:08.955
Can you imagine what he's
going through up there?

344
00:34:09.155 --> 00:34:12.425
I mean. he's 50 million miles away from home.
He thinks he's totally alone.

345
00:34:12.525 --> 00:34:14.853
He thinks we gave up on him.

346
00:34:14.953 --> 00:34:18.173
What does that do to a man.
psychologically?

347
00:34:19.240 --> 00:34:21.070
What the hell is he thinking right now?

348
00:34:21.170 --> 00:34:23.729
(DISCO MUSIC PLAYING)

349
00:34:24.956 --> 00:34:27.975
I'm definitely gonna die up here...

350
00:34:28.075 --> 00:34:32.104
if I have to listen to any more
god-awful disco music.

351
00:34:32.504 --> 00:34:36.758
My God. Commander Lewis. couldn't you
have packed anything from this century?

352
00:34:38.953 --> 00:34:41.139
No. I am not gonna
"turn the beat around."

353
00:34:41.239 --> 00:34:43.058
- I refuse to.
- (MUSIC STOPS)

354
00:34:43.158 --> 00:34:45.836
- (REPORTERS CLAMORING)
- Mr. Sanders? Mr. Sanders?

355
00:34:47.004 --> 00:34:49.980
What attempts have been made
to make contact with Mark Watney?

356
00:34:50.080 --> 00:34:51.699
We're working on it.

357
00:34:51.799 --> 00:34:55.537
- Does he have enough supplies to survive?
- We'll be looking into that.

358
00:34:55.637 --> 00:34:58.557
What does this say about the agency?
Are you gonna resign?

359
00:34:58.657 --> 00:35:00.609
- No.
- Director Sanders!

360
00:35:05.256 --> 00:35:08.051
WATNEY: It's time to start
thinking long term.

361
00:35:08.151 --> 00:35:10.411
The next NASA mission is Ares 4

362
00:35:10.511 --> 00:35:13.056
and it's supposed to land
at Schiaparelli Crater

363
00:35:13.156 --> 00:35:15.600
3200 kilometers away.

364
00:35:15.700 --> 00:35:19.983
3.200 kilometers.

365
00:35:20.083 --> 00:35:24.960
In four years. when the next Ares crew
arrives. I'll have to be there.

366
00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:27.833
Which means I have to get to the crater.

367
00:35:29.348 --> 00:35:31.242
Okay. so here's the rub.

368
00:35:31.342 --> 00:35:36.089
I've got one working Rover designed
to go a max distance of 35 kilometers

369
00:35:36.189 --> 00:35:39.951
before the battery has to be
recharged at the Hab.

370
00:35:40.051 --> 00:35:41.577
That's Problem A.

371
00:35:42.378 --> 00:35:44.200
Problem B...

372
00:35:44.300 --> 00:35:48.978
is this journey's gonna take me
roughly 50 days to complete.

373
00:35:49.078 --> 00:35:51.797
So I gotta live for 50 days

374
00:35:51.898 --> 00:35:56.518
inside a Rover with marginal life
support the size of a small van.

375
00:35:56.618 --> 00:35:58.004
So...

376
00:35:58.104 --> 00:36:02.042
in the face of overwhelming odds.
I'm left with only one option.

377
00:36:02.542 --> 00:36:05.442
I'm gonna have to science
the shit out of this.

378
00:36:32.440 --> 00:36:35.510
Okay. so. success.

379
00:36:36.336 --> 00:36:38.145
Uh...

380
00:36:39.915 --> 00:36:44.396
I have doubled my battery life
by scavenging Rover 1.

381
00:36:45.087 --> 00:36:49.024
But... if I use the heater...

382
00:36:49.324 --> 00:36:54.623
I will burn through half
my battery every day.

383
00:36:55.390 --> 00:37:00.178
If I do not use my heater. I will be...
(LAUGHS)

384
00:37:00.278 --> 00:37:03.389
slowly killed by the laws
of thermodynamics.

385
00:37:03.789 --> 00:37:08.930
I would love to solve this problem
right now but... unfortunately...

386
00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:12.078
my balls are frozen.

387
00:37:13.450 --> 00:37:16.391
I can't. I'm calling it. I'm calling it.

388
00:37:27.715 --> 00:37:31.111
Good news. I may have a solution
to my heating problem.

389
00:37:31.611 --> 00:37:36.605
Bad news. it involves me digging up
the Radioisotope Thermoelectric Generator.

390
00:37:36.705 --> 00:37:40.638
Now. if I remember my training correctly.
one of the lessons was titled

391
00:37:40.738 --> 00:37:43.917
"Don't dig up the big box
of plutonium. Mark."

392
00:37:44.017 --> 00:37:48.154
I get it. RTGs are good for spacecraft.
but if they rupture around humans...

393
00:37:48.254 --> 00:37:51.808
no more humans. which is why
we buried it when we arrived.

394
00:37:51.908 --> 00:37:54.727
And planted that flag so we
would never be stupid enough

395
00:37:54.828 --> 00:37:57.089
to accidentally go near it again.

396
00:37:57.189 --> 00:38:00.067
But as long as I don't break it...

397
00:38:00.367 --> 00:38:02.987
(CHUCKLES) I almost just said
"Everything will be fine" out loud.

398
00:38:03.087 --> 00:38:05.447
Look. the point is.
I'm not cold anymore.

399
00:38:05.547 --> 00:38:08.692
And sure. I could choose to think
about the fact that I'm warm

400
00:38:08.792 --> 00:38:12.780
because I have a decaying
radioactive isotope riding right behind me

401
00:38:12.881 --> 00:38:15.133
but right now. I got
bigger problems on my hands.

402
00:38:15.333 --> 00:38:20.063
I have scoured every single data file
on Commander Lewis' personal drive.

403
00:38:20.163 --> 00:38:25.101
This is officially
the least disco song she owns.

404
00:38:25.201 --> 00:38:29.465
WOMAN: <i>Lookin' for some hot stuff.
baby. this evenin'</i>

405
00:38:29.565 --> 00:38:33.349
<i>I need some hot stuff. baby. tonight</i>

406
00:38:33.449 --> 00:38:37.974
<i>I want some hot stuff.
baby. this evenin'</i>

407
00:38:38.074 --> 00:38:42.078
<i>Gotta have some hot stuff
Gotta have some love tonight</i>

408
00:38:42.178 --> 00:38:44.448
<i>Hot stuff</i>

409
00:38:45.398 --> 00:38:48.429
<i>I need hot stuff</i>

410
00:38:49.444 --> 00:38:51.866
<i>I want some hot stuff</i>

411
00:38:53.406 --> 00:38:56.344
<i>I need hot stuff...</i>

412
00:38:59.387 --> 00:39:00.798
- Yeah.
- Where is Watney going?

413
00:39:00.899 --> 00:39:03.301
We believe that he's preparing
for a journey.

414
00:39:03.401 --> 00:39:05.487
He's been conducting incremental tests

415
00:39:05.587 --> 00:39:08.477
taking the Rover 2 out for longer
and longer trips each time.

416
00:39:08.577 --> 00:39:10.674
- (REPORTERS CLAMORING)
- Yeah?

417
00:39:10.774 --> 00:39:13.427
To what end? Why would he leave
the relative safety of the Hab?

418
00:39:13.527 --> 00:39:16.731
Well. we think that he plans to travel
to the Ares 4 launch site

419
00:39:16.832 --> 00:39:19.927
in order to make contact with us.
but it would be a dangerous gamble.

420
00:39:20.027 --> 00:39:22.704
But if we could talk to him.
we would tell him to stay put

421
00:39:22.805 --> 00:39:27.351
and to trust that we are doing everything
in our power to bring him home alive.

422
00:39:27.451 --> 00:39:29.194
Thank you very much.

423
00:39:29.294 --> 00:39:31.371
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

424
00:39:31.972 --> 00:39:36.219
- Don't say "Bring him home alive." Vincent.
- You know. these interviews aren't easy.

425
00:39:36.319 --> 00:39:39.873
So God forbid I try to say
something proactive and positive.

426
00:39:39.973 --> 00:39:43.093
- SANDERS: Annie.
- No more Vincent on TV. Copy that.

427
00:39:43.493 --> 00:39:46.471
76 kilometers. Am I reading that right?

428
00:39:46.972 --> 00:39:49.350
- MINDY: Are you asking me?
- SANDERS: I am.

429
00:39:49.450 --> 00:39:50.776
Yes. sir.

430
00:39:50.877 --> 00:39:54.847
Mark drove two hours straightaway
from the Hab. did a short EVA

431
00:39:54.947 --> 00:39:58.810
and then drove for another two.
We think the EVA was to change batteries.

432
00:39:58.910 --> 00:40:01.721
He didn't load up the oxygenator
or the water reclaimer?

433
00:40:01.821 --> 00:40:04.156
Every 41 hours. there's a 17 minute gap.

434
00:40:04.256 --> 00:40:09.587
It's just the way the orbits work so...
it's possible that we missed something.

435
00:40:09.687 --> 00:40:11.539
I want that gap down to four minutes.

436
00:40:11.639 --> 00:40:15.811
I'm giving you total authority over satellite
trajectories and orbital adjustments.

437
00:40:15.911 --> 00:40:18.864
- Make it happen.
- Okay.

438
00:40:18.964 --> 00:40:24.562
Let's assume Miss Park didn't miss anything.
So Mark's not going to Ares 4. Yet.

439
00:40:24.662 --> 00:40:28.137
But he's smart enough to figure out
that's his only chance.

440
00:40:28.237 --> 00:40:31.194
Bruce. what's the earliest
we can get a pre-supply there?

441
00:40:31.294 --> 00:40:34.105
Well. with the positions
of Earth and Mars.

442
00:40:34.205 --> 00:40:36.174
it'll take nine months.

443
00:40:36.274 --> 00:40:38.678
It'll take six months
to build it in the first place.

444
00:40:38.819 --> 00:40:41.438
- Three months.
- Three? That's...

445
00:40:41.538 --> 00:40:42.956
SANDERS:
You're going to say it's impossible

446
00:40:43.056 --> 00:40:46.710
and then I'm gonna make a speech about
the blinding capabilities of the JPL team

447
00:40:46.811 --> 00:40:49.418
and then you're going to do the math
in your head and say something like.

448
00:40:49.518 --> 00:40:53.475
- "The overtime alone will be a nightmare."
- The overtime alone will be a nightmare.

449
00:40:53.575 --> 00:40:55.954
Get started. I'll find you the money.

450
00:40:57.355 --> 00:41:00.216
- We need to tell the crew.
- VINCENT: Mitch. we've discussed this.

451
00:41:00.316 --> 00:41:05.030
No. you discussed this. I'm the one
who decides what's best for the crew.

452
00:41:06.531 --> 00:41:08.872
They deserve to know.

453
00:41:09.319 --> 00:41:12.646
Once there's a real rescue plan.
we'll tell them. otherwise. it's moot.

454
00:41:13.047 --> 00:41:17.684
Bruce has three months to get the payload
done. That's all that matters right now.

455
00:41:17.784 --> 00:41:21.781
- We'll do our best.
- Mark dies if you don't.

456
00:41:23.240 --> 00:41:26.686
WATNEY: It's been 48 sols since
I planted the potatoes. So...

457
00:41:26.786 --> 00:41:29.156
now it's time to reap and re-sow.

458
00:41:29.256 --> 00:41:31.524
They grew even better than I expected.

459
00:41:31.624 --> 00:41:35.095
I now have 400 healthy potato plants.

460
00:41:35.195 --> 00:41:38.165
I dug them up. being careful
to leave their plants alive.

461
00:41:38.265 --> 00:41:42.452
The smaller ones I'll reseed.
the larger ones are my food supply.

462
00:41:42.552 --> 00:41:46.174
All natural. organic.
Martian-grown potatoes.

463
00:41:46.274 --> 00:41:49.133
You don't hear that every day. do you?

464
00:41:49.233 --> 00:41:51.012
And by the way.
none of this matters at all

465
00:41:51.112 --> 00:41:54.687
if I can't figure out a way
to make contact with NASA.

466
00:42:15.796 --> 00:42:18.322
I know what I'm gonna do.

467
00:42:45.794 --> 00:42:49.674
- Oh! He's moving again.
- Where the hell is he going?

468
00:42:49.774 --> 00:42:54.012
He hasn't changed course for 13 days.
He's nowhere near the Ares 4.

469
00:42:54.612 --> 00:42:57.980
Well. unless he's not taking a direct route.
I mean. he might be trying to...

470
00:42:58.080 --> 00:43:01.937
- avoid some obstacle.
- What obstacle?

471
00:43:02.387 --> 00:43:06.918
It's Acidalia Planitia.
There's nothing out there except the...

472
00:43:08.161 --> 00:43:09.914
What?

473
00:43:12.849 --> 00:43:14.607
I need a map.

474
00:43:15.685 --> 00:43:19.096
Okay. Okay.

475
00:43:21.091 --> 00:43:22.767
Yeah.

476
00:43:22.868 --> 00:43:26.630
- Hey. come on. man. What are you doing?
- It's all right. Can I borrow this?

477
00:43:26.730 --> 00:43:31.585
- Okay. so where is the Hab location?
- 31.2 degrees north. 28.5 degrees west.

478
00:43:31.685 --> 00:43:36.104
- Okay. Mmm-hmm. Where's Watney?
- Uh... There.

479
00:43:36.204 --> 00:43:38.032
VINCENT: Okay.

480
00:43:43.473 --> 00:43:45.085
Okay.

481
00:43:45.185 --> 00:43:48.029
I know where he's going.
I need to get on an airplane.

482
00:43:55.269 --> 00:43:57.255
(PANTING)

483
00:44:20.362 --> 00:44:23.473
- Vincent. how are you?
- Good to see you.

484
00:44:23.573 --> 00:44:25.994
- Good flight?
- Uh... Yeah.

485
00:44:26.794 --> 00:44:29.370
It's in storage just around the corner.

486
00:45:03.666 --> 00:45:06.136
- Hey. Vincent. nice to see you again.
- Nice to see you.

487
00:45:06.236 --> 00:45:08.613
What are the chances Mark
can get it working again?

488
00:45:08.713 --> 00:45:12.224
It's hard to say.
We lost contact in '97.

489
00:45:12.324 --> 00:45:14.578
We think it was battery failure.

490
00:45:14.678 --> 00:45:18.182
Though I'd like to point out it lasted
three times longer than expected...

491
00:45:18.282 --> 00:45:19.876
Nobody's criticizing JPL's work. Bruce.

492
00:45:19.976 --> 00:45:21.969
I just need to speak to everybody
that was here in '97.

493
00:45:22.069 --> 00:45:25.547
They're already here. Guys.
I'd like to introduce Vincent Kapoor.

494
00:45:25.647 --> 00:45:27.383
Director of Mars Missions for NASA.

495
00:45:27.483 --> 00:45:31.485
This is our current team...
and our original project members.

496
00:45:47.446 --> 00:45:48.797
- Is this the replica?
- TECHNICIAN: This is her.

497
00:45:48.898 --> 00:45:50.992
Okay. Let's see it.

498
00:45:51.792 --> 00:45:53.119
Pathfinder.

499
00:45:58.716 --> 00:46:00.068
Pathfinder.

500
00:46:40.394 --> 00:46:41.949
(WHIRRING)

501
00:47:10.960 --> 00:47:12.853
Come on. Come on.

502
00:47:13.762 --> 00:47:15.777
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

503
00:47:19.760 --> 00:47:21.763
(BEEPING)

504
00:47:31.648 --> 00:47:33.308
(BEEPING)

505
00:47:33.708 --> 00:47:36.145
Holy shit. Okay.

506
00:47:36.445 --> 00:47:38.998
"Broadcasting status.
Listening for telemetry signal."

507
00:47:39.098 --> 00:47:40.867
Uh-huh.

508
00:47:40.967 --> 00:47:43.253
- TIM: Okay. Signal acquired.
- (VINCENT LAUGHING)

509
00:47:44.645 --> 00:47:47.966
- VINCENT: All right.
- TIM: Okay. Camera.

510
00:48:35.591 --> 00:48:36.684
(BEEPING)

511
00:48:36.784 --> 00:48:38.093
Incoming.

512
00:48:40.554 --> 00:48:43.716
"Are you receiving me?"

513
00:48:44.017 --> 00:48:46.120
"Yes. No."

514
00:48:46.220 --> 00:48:47.963
(CHUCKLES)

515
00:48:48.063 --> 00:48:50.407
Okay. point the camera at "yes."

516
00:48:50.507 --> 00:48:52.918
32-minute round-trip
communications time.

517
00:48:53.018 --> 00:48:56.188
All he can do is ask yes or no questions
and all we can do is point the camera.

518
00:48:56.288 --> 00:48:59.102
This won't exactly be an Algonquin
Round Table of snappy repartee.

519
00:48:59.202 --> 00:49:01.019
- Are you kidding me?
- Tim. Tim.

520
00:49:01.119 --> 00:49:05.667
- Just point the camera.
- Roger that. Pointing the camera.

521
00:49:17.010 --> 00:49:18.937
Whoo!

522
00:49:20.431 --> 00:49:22.291
Yes!

523
00:49:23.092 --> 00:49:24.902
Yes!

524
00:49:25.402 --> 00:49:27.679
So here's the rub.

525
00:49:27.779 --> 00:49:29.999
Somehow we have to have complex

526
00:49:30.099 --> 00:49:33.120
- astrophysical engineering conversations...
- (MICROWAVE TIMER BEEPING)

527
00:49:33.220 --> 00:49:36.974
using nothing
but a still-frame camera...

528
00:49:37.074 --> 00:49:39.633
from 1996.

529
00:49:42.112 --> 00:49:43.964
Luckily...

530
00:49:45.165 --> 00:49:46.950
the camera does spin.

531
00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:49.904
So I can make an alphabet.

532
00:49:50.004 --> 00:49:51.823
It can't be our alphabet.

533
00:49:51.923 --> 00:49:56.769
26 characters plus a question card
into 360 gives us 13 degrees of arc.

534
00:49:56.869 --> 00:50:01.115
That's way too narrow. I'd never know
what the camera was pointing at.

535
00:50:07.706 --> 00:50:09.579
Ooh.

536
00:50:13.487 --> 00:50:15.494
Hexadecimals.

537
00:50:19.118 --> 00:50:21.224
Hexadecimals to the rescue.

538
00:50:21.324 --> 00:50:24.991
I figured one of you guys
kept an ASCII table lying around.

539
00:50:25.091 --> 00:50:30.663
And I was right. Ladies and gentlemen.
I give you super-nerd Beth Johanssen.

540
00:50:30.763 --> 00:50:33.708
Who also had copies of Zork II

541
00:50:33.809 --> 00:50:36.702
and Leather Goddesses of Phobos
on her personal laptop.

542
00:50:36.803 --> 00:50:37.996
(LAUGHING)

543
00:50:38.096 --> 00:50:42.418
Seriously. Johanssen. it's like
the Smithsonian of loneliness on there.

544
00:50:42.518 --> 00:50:44.245
Not that I'm complaining. Yes!

545
00:50:44.345 --> 00:50:46.957
Who am I to talk about loneliness?

546
00:51:06.776 --> 00:51:09.426
I know where he's going with this.

547
00:51:37.827 --> 00:51:38.863
(MOANS SOFTLY)

548
00:51:56.972 --> 00:51:59.282
"F. O."

549
00:51:59.382 --> 00:52:01.866
"7. W."

550
00:52:17.785 --> 00:52:19.046
(BEEPING)

551
00:52:19.146 --> 00:52:22.584
- Vincent. Vincent. wake up.
- (GROANS)

552
00:52:33.937 --> 00:52:36.543
Now that we can have more
complicated conversations

553
00:52:36.643 --> 00:52:39.333
the smart people at NASA
have sent me instructions

554
00:52:39.433 --> 00:52:43.017
on how to hack the Rover
so that it can talk to Pathfinder.

555
00:52:43.117 --> 00:52:47.918
If I hack a tiny bit of code just 20
instructions in the Rover's operating system

556
00:52:48.018 --> 00:52:52.264
NASA can link the Rover to Pathfinder's
broadcasting frequency

557
00:52:52.364 --> 00:52:54.601
and we're in business.

558
00:53:08.444 --> 00:53:11.810
"Mark. this is Vincent Kapoor.

559
00:53:11.910 --> 00:53:15.194
"We've been watching you since Sol 54.

560
00:53:16.372 --> 00:53:19.509
"The whole world is rooting for you.

561
00:53:19.609 --> 00:53:23.064
"Amazing job getting Pathfinder.

562
00:53:23.164 --> 00:53:25.191
"We're working on rescue plans.

563
00:53:25.641 --> 00:53:28.752
"Meantime. we're putting together
a supply mission

564
00:53:28.853 --> 00:53:30.749
"to keep you fed...

565
00:53:30.850 --> 00:53:34.690
"until Ares 4 arrives."

566
00:53:50.550 --> 00:53:52.354
Okay.

567
00:54:00.453 --> 00:54:01.462
(BEEPING)

568
00:54:01.562 --> 00:54:05.641
Okay. "Glad to hear it.
Really looking forward to not dying."

569
00:54:05.741 --> 00:54:07.182
(ALL LAUGHING)

570
00:54:07.282 --> 00:54:08.594
(APPLAUSE)

571
00:54:18.263 --> 00:54:22.184
"How's the crew? What did they say
when they found out I was alive?"

572
00:54:43.465 --> 00:54:45.726
Guys. can we get some space please?

573
00:54:46.227 --> 00:54:48.304
- Me?
- Yeah. you.

574
00:54:48.404 --> 00:54:50.664
Just give me a sec.

575
00:54:56.262 --> 00:54:58.331
Just tell him.

576
00:55:06.331 --> 00:55:09.645
"We haven't told the crew...

577
00:55:09.745 --> 00:55:12.203
"you are alive yet.

578
00:55:13.789 --> 00:55:18.243
"We need them to concentrate
on their mission."

579
00:55:22.941 --> 00:55:25.005
(EXHALES)

580
00:55:31.075 --> 00:55:33.476
(MOUTHING) What the fuck?

581
00:55:34.203 --> 00:55:36.281
What the fuck?

582
00:55:42.611 --> 00:55:45.364
Okay. he says.
"They don't know I'm alive?

583
00:55:45.464 --> 00:55:48.501
"What the" F-word.
F-word in gerund form.

584
00:55:48.601 --> 00:55:51.629
- F-word. again. "is wrong with you?"
- (ALL LAUGHING)

585
00:55:52.831 --> 00:55:56.417
"Mark. please watch your language.

586
00:55:56.517 --> 00:56:02.603
"Everything you type is being
broadcast live all over the world."

587
00:56:05.377 --> 00:56:07.213
Yeah?

588
00:56:13.327 --> 00:56:14.686
(ALL GASPING)

589
00:56:14.786 --> 00:56:17.382
VINCENT: Oh. my God. (SIGHS)

590
00:56:18.365 --> 00:56:22.042
SANDERS: Yes. sir. He is under
a tremendous amount of stress.

591
00:56:23.080 --> 00:56:26.766
I understand. We're working on it.
I'm sure he didn't mean what he said.

592
00:56:26.867 --> 00:56:29.336
Thank you. Mr. President.

593
00:56:30.578 --> 00:56:34.391
Problem is. Mark's right. The longer
we wait. the worse it's gonna get.

594
00:56:34.491 --> 00:56:35.676
We need to tell the crew.

595
00:56:35.776 --> 00:56:39.856
You're bringing this up while Vincent is in
Pasadena so he can't argue the other side.

596
00:56:39.956 --> 00:56:43.813
I shouldn't have to answer to Vincent.
Or anyone else.

597
00:56:45.569 --> 00:56:47.096
It's time. Teddy.

598
00:57:10.013 --> 00:57:11.006
(BEEPING)

599
00:57:11.106 --> 00:57:14.592
- JOHANSSEN: Commander Lewis?
- Go ahead.

600
00:57:14.692 --> 00:57:17.103
JOHANSSEN: Data dump is almost complete.

601
00:57:17.203 --> 00:57:19.367
Copy that. On my way.

602
00:57:32.253 --> 00:57:35.091
- You're in a hurry.
- MARTINEZ: Yeah.

603
00:57:35.191 --> 00:57:39.464
My son turned three yesterday.
Should be pictures of the party.

604
00:57:49.734 --> 00:57:54.554
JOHANSSEN: Got a batch of personals.
Dispatching them to your laptops now.

605
00:57:54.968 --> 00:57:58.364
I don't need to read Vogel's
weird German fetish emails.

606
00:57:58.464 --> 00:58:02.576
- VOGEL: They're telemetry updates.
- Hey. whatever does it for you. man.

607
00:58:02.676 --> 00:58:06.764
Oh. there's a video message.
It's addressed to the whole crew.

608
00:58:06.865 --> 00:58:08.774
LEWIS: Play it. Come on. guys.

609
00:58:09.375 --> 00:58:11.085
BECK:
I wanna get in on that telemetry action.

610
00:58:11.185 --> 00:58:13.219
(MEN LAUGHING)

611
00:58:14.965 --> 00:58:18.318
Hi. hello. It's Mitch. Mitch Henderson.

612
00:58:18.418 --> 00:58:22.931
I have some news.
There's no subtle way to put this.

613
00:58:23.740 --> 00:58:27.669
- Mark Watney is still alive.
- Oh. my God.

614
00:58:27.769 --> 00:58:31.424
I know that's a surprise and I know
you will have a lot of questions.

615
00:58:31.825 --> 00:58:34.485
But here are the basics. He's...

616
00:58:34.585 --> 00:58:37.080
He's alive and he's healthy.

617
00:58:37.180 --> 00:58:42.477
We... we found out two months ago
and decided not to tell you.

618
00:58:42.577 --> 00:58:43.937
- Two months?
- Oh. my God.

619
00:58:44.137 --> 00:58:46.573
MITCH:
I was strongly against that decision.

620
00:58:46.673 --> 00:58:49.663
We're telling you now because...

621
00:58:49.763 --> 00:58:52.346
we finally have
communication with him...

622
00:58:52.446 --> 00:58:55.374
and a viable rescue plan.

623
00:58:55.474 --> 00:58:59.261
We'll give you a write-up of what happened.
a full write-up of everything.

624
00:58:59.361 --> 00:59:03.560
But it's not your fault. Mark
stresses that every time it comes up.

625
00:59:04.818 --> 00:59:07.855
So... yeah.

626
00:59:09.247 --> 00:59:11.591
Take some time to absorb this.

627
00:59:11.691 --> 00:59:16.342
And send all the questions you want.
We'll answer them.

628
00:59:17.323 --> 00:59:20.894
- All right. Henderson out.
- BECK: Holy shit. he's alive.

629
00:59:22.095 --> 00:59:23.671
- I left him behind.
- JOHANSSEN: No.

630
00:59:23.771 --> 00:59:26.149
BECK: No. We all left together.

631
00:59:26.249 --> 00:59:28.777
You were following orders.

632
00:59:31.704 --> 00:59:33.549
I left him behind.

633
00:59:43.058 --> 00:59:46.070
WATNEY: So now that NASA
can talk to me. they won't shut up.

634
00:59:46.170 --> 00:59:49.123
They want constant updates
on every Hab system

635
00:59:49.223 --> 00:59:53.036
and they got a room full of people
trying to micromanage my crops.

636
00:59:53.136 --> 00:59:55.263
Which is awesome.

637
00:59:55.363 --> 00:59:58.542
Look. I don't mean to sound arrogant
or anything but I am...

638
00:59:58.642 --> 01:00:02.909
the greatest botanist
on this planet. so...

639
01:00:03.696 --> 01:00:07.539
Oh. one big bonus to this communication
with NASA again. is the email.

640
01:00:07.639 --> 01:00:11.105
I'm getting them again. Big data dumps
like when I was on the Hermes.

641
01:00:11.205 --> 01:00:13.049
I even got one from the president.

642
01:00:13.149 --> 01:00:15.617
The coolest one. though.
the coolest one I got

643
01:00:15.717 --> 01:00:18.403
was from University of Chicago.
my Alma mater.

644
01:00:18.720 --> 01:00:24.002
They say that once you grow crops
somewhere you've officially colonized it.

645
01:00:24.102 --> 01:00:27.059
So. technically...

646
01:00:27.497 --> 01:00:30.131
- I colonized Mars.
- ("ROCK THE BOAT" PLAYING)

647
01:00:33.896 --> 01:00:36.481
In your face. Neil Armstrong.

648
01:00:36.581 --> 01:00:40.469
In other news. there's been a request
for me to pose for a photograph

649
01:00:40.569 --> 01:00:42.907
on my next transmission.

650
01:00:43.372 --> 01:00:47.643
I'm trying to figure out whether
I should go with "High School Senior"

651
01:00:47.743 --> 01:00:52.214
or "coquettish ingenue." But...

652
01:00:52.849 --> 01:00:55.370
I'm not really sure how that's
gonna look with my spacesuit on.

653
01:01:02.935 --> 01:01:04.868
(BEEPING)

654
01:01:21.796 --> 01:01:23.874
Hey!

655
01:01:25.491 --> 01:01:29.096
What is he doing? I asked for a photo.
and what. he's The Fonz?

656
01:01:29.196 --> 01:01:31.132
Just be grateful
we got you something. Annie.

657
01:01:31.232 --> 01:01:34.460
I can't use this. Vincent. and you know that.
I need a picture of his face.

658
01:01:34.760 --> 01:01:37.997
Well. I could tell him to take off his helmet
but then he'd. you know. die. so...

659
01:01:38.097 --> 01:01:39.481
(ALL LAUGHING)

660
01:01:39.581 --> 01:01:41.901
SANDERS: We'll release the photo
when we detail the rescue operation.

661
01:01:42.001 --> 01:01:45.230
I want to announce we're launching
some supplies to him next year

662
01:01:45.330 --> 01:01:47.240
during the Hohmann Transfer Window.

663
01:01:47.340 --> 01:01:51.736
- Bruce. your team's still on schedule?
- It'll be tight. but we'll make it.

664
01:01:51.837 --> 01:01:56.016
Nine-month travel time.
That puts the probe to Mars on Sol 868.

665
01:01:56.116 --> 01:01:57.750
Did we get the botany team's analysis?

666
01:01:57.851 --> 01:02:01.305
Yeah. they estimate Mark's crops
will last till Sol 912.

667
01:02:01.405 --> 01:02:04.150
They grudgingly admit
that he's doing great work.

668
01:02:04.250 --> 01:02:06.487
- Grudgingly?
- Yeah. Mark has a tendency to tell them

669
01:02:06.587 --> 01:02:09.697
to have sex with themselves whenever
they question one of his decisions.

670
01:02:09.797 --> 01:02:12.901
SANDERS: Get him in line. Vincent.
We can't afford any miscommunication.

671
01:02:13.001 --> 01:02:18.659
I hate this margin. 912 Sols
worth of food. We get there on 868.

672
01:02:19.074 --> 01:02:21.777
And that's assuming nothing goes wrong.

673
01:02:45.451 --> 01:02:47.555
- (ALARM BLARING)
- (AIR HISSING)

674
01:02:51.625 --> 01:02:53.675
(SCREAMING)

675
01:02:56.964 --> 01:02:59.000
(GROANING)

676
01:03:05.023 --> 01:03:06.674
(GROANS)

677
01:03:06.774 --> 01:03:09.420
AUTOMATED VOICE: Suit breach detected.

678
01:03:09.520 --> 01:03:11.546
(PANTING)

679
01:03:16.969 --> 01:03:19.983
Oxygen level critical.

680
01:03:33.086 --> 01:03:36.483
Oxygen level. 10%.

681
01:03:50.404 --> 01:03:53.746
Oxygen level. 5%.

682
01:04:02.458 --> 01:04:05.450
Suit pressure. stable.

683
01:04:22.738 --> 01:04:24.713
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

684
01:05:36.600 --> 01:05:38.640
(CONTINUES BREATHING HEAVILY)

685
01:06:00.275 --> 01:06:02.695
AUTOMATED VOICE: Pressure stable.

686
01:06:18.602 --> 01:06:20.656
(BLOWING)

687
01:06:35.688 --> 01:06:39.301
God! God. God. God. God!

688
01:06:57.603 --> 01:06:59.471
Crops are dead.

689
01:06:59.571 --> 01:07:01.808
Complete loss of pressure
boiled off most of the water.

690
01:07:01.908 --> 01:07:04.977
Any bacteria that survived.
died in the subzero temperatures

691
01:07:05.077 --> 01:07:07.238
when exposed to Mars' atmosphere.

692
01:07:07.338 --> 01:07:09.516
- ANNIE: How long does he have?
- (SIGHS)

693
01:07:10.250 --> 01:07:14.296
He can still eat the potatoes he has.
he just can't grow any more. so...

694
01:07:14.396 --> 01:07:16.849
get him 200 sols.

695
01:07:17.149 --> 01:07:20.013
Rations get him to what? Sol 409?

696
01:07:20.113 --> 01:07:23.138
Mmm-hmm. So with potatoes. 609.

697
01:07:23.238 --> 01:07:25.959
So by Sol 868. he'll be long dead.

698
01:07:26.059 --> 01:07:30.591
We're gonna have to launch as soon
as possible which changes our travel time.

699
01:07:30.930 --> 01:07:33.374
Yeah. we're working on it.

700
01:07:33.474 --> 01:07:37.710
Prelim estimates call
for a 414-day trip.

701
01:07:38.079 --> 01:07:40.257
It's Sol 135 now.

702
01:07:40.357 --> 01:07:42.426
We need 13 days to mount the boosters.

703
01:07:42.526 --> 01:07:46.780
perform inspections which gives
Bruce and his team...

704
01:07:47.281 --> 01:07:50.393
47 days to make this probe.

705
01:07:50.826 --> 01:07:54.039
I'll let you call Bruce.
give him the news.

706
01:07:57.258 --> 01:07:59.064
Okay.

707
01:08:01.779 --> 01:08:04.164
I'm gonna need a change of clothes.

708
01:08:12.809 --> 01:08:15.027
MARTINEZ: "Dear Mark...

709
01:08:15.127 --> 01:08:20.434
"Apparently... NASA's letting us
talk to you now.

710
01:08:21.025 --> 01:08:24.386
"And I drew the short straw.

711
01:08:27.031 --> 01:08:28.107
(CHUCKLES)

712
01:08:28.207 --> 01:08:31.837
"Sorry we left you behind on Mars.

713
01:08:32.237 --> 01:08:35.023
"But we just don't like you.

714
01:08:35.123 --> 01:08:36.825
(ALL CHUCKLING)

715
01:08:36.925 --> 01:08:42.083
"Also. it's a lot roomier
on the Hermes without you.

716
01:08:42.789 --> 01:08:46.169
"We have to take turns doing your tasks.

717
01:08:46.970 --> 01:08:50.460
"But. I mean. it's only botany.

718
01:08:50.560 --> 01:08:51.524
(LAUGHING)

719
01:08:51.624 --> 01:08:54.768
- "It's not real science."
- Oh. Jesus.

720
01:08:56.170 --> 01:08:58.410
"How's Mars?"

721
01:09:01.911 --> 01:09:06.473
WATNEY: "Dear Martinez. Mars is fine.

722
01:09:06.573 --> 01:09:09.406
"I accidentally blew up the Hab

723
01:09:09.506 --> 01:09:14.241
"but unfortunately.
all of Commander Lewis' disco music

724
01:09:14.341 --> 01:09:15.912
"still survived."

725
01:09:16.550 --> 01:09:21.289
"But unfortunately. all of Commander
Lewis' disco music still survived."

726
01:09:21.389 --> 01:09:26.677
WATNEY: "Every day. I go outside
and look at the vast horizons."

727
01:09:26.777 --> 01:09:30.473
MARTINEZ: "Every day. I go outside
and look at the vast horizons."

728
01:09:30.573 --> 01:09:32.625
WATNEY: "Just because I can."

729
01:09:32.725 --> 01:09:34.896
MARTINEZ: "Just because I can.

730
01:09:34.996 --> 01:09:38.188
"Tell the others I said hello."

731
01:09:40.943 --> 01:09:43.054
"Will do. buddy."

732
01:09:51.150 --> 01:09:52.782
(CHUCKLES SADLY)

733
01:10:59.635 --> 01:11:01.706
(MACHINERY POWERING UP)

734
01:11:12.357 --> 01:11:14.837
AUTOMATED VOICE: Pressure stable.

735
01:11:39.903 --> 01:11:41.903
(WIND HOWLING)

736
01:11:45.242 --> 01:11:47.302
(PLASTIC RUSTLING)

737
01:11:53.934 --> 01:11:56.753
5. 10...

738
01:11:56.854 --> 01:12:00.926
15. 20. 30. 35... (SIGHS DEEPLY)

739
01:12:01.026 --> 01:12:02.102
40.

740
01:12:02.903 --> 01:12:04.820
52.

741
01:12:16.092 --> 01:12:17.420
(GROANS LOUDLY)

742
01:12:32.993 --> 01:12:34.828
Rich.

743
01:12:35.528 --> 01:12:38.290
Rich. Wake up.

744
01:12:40.208 --> 01:12:42.577
Sorry. but they're asking
for the probe courses.

745
01:12:42.677 --> 01:12:46.539
- What time is it?
- It's 3:42.

746
01:12:47.440 --> 01:12:49.460
(SPITS)

747
01:12:50.061 --> 01:12:51.187
(CLATTERS)

748
01:12:51.587 --> 01:12:54.073
Look. I know we're coming
at this backwards

749
01:12:54.173 --> 01:12:57.260
but we can't commit to a firm launch
date with this many unknowns.

750
01:12:58.361 --> 01:13:00.213
It's all right. Um...

751
01:13:00.313 --> 01:13:03.049
All 25 models for launch
will take 414 days to reach Mars.

752
01:13:03.149 --> 01:13:06.732
They vary slightly in thrust duration and
the fuel requirement is nearly identical.

753
01:13:08.088 --> 01:13:10.115
Not a good time to launch. is it?

754
01:13:10.215 --> 01:13:13.135
Yeah. Earth and Mars
are really badly positioned.

755
01:13:13.235 --> 01:13:15.956
Heck. it'd almost be easier
if you. um...

756
01:13:17.948 --> 01:13:20.442
Almost easier to what?

757
01:13:20.542 --> 01:13:22.829
I need more coffee. (THUDS)

758
01:13:23.930 --> 01:13:26.701
- MIKE: Are you all right?
- It's fine.

759
01:13:30.711 --> 01:13:33.107
Almost easier to what?

760
01:13:43.700 --> 01:13:46.480
You do understand I'm your boss. right?

761
01:13:46.703 --> 01:13:48.490
Uh-huh.

762
01:13:51.475 --> 01:13:55.780
SANDERS: All right. let's ask
the very. very expensive question.

763
01:13:55.881 --> 01:13:58.416
- Is the probe going to be ready on time?
- BRUCE: We're behind.

764
01:13:58.516 --> 01:14:02.537
- Give me a number.
- 15 days. 15 days and I can get it done.

765
01:14:02.637 --> 01:14:07.284
All right. let's create 15 days. 13 days
to mount the probe. Can we reduce?

766
01:14:07.384 --> 01:14:09.712
It actually only takes
three days to mount the probe.

767
01:14:09.813 --> 01:14:13.141
- And we can get that down to two. right?
- I can get it down to two.

768
01:14:13.241 --> 01:14:14.951
10 days are for tests and inspections.

769
01:14:15.051 --> 01:14:18.288
How often do those inspections
reveal a problem?

770
01:14:18.388 --> 01:14:20.314
Are you suggesting
we don't do the inspections?

771
01:14:20.414 --> 01:14:22.834
Right now I'm asking how often
they reveal a problem.

772
01:14:23.034 --> 01:14:24.110
One in 20.

773
01:14:24.210 --> 01:14:26.997
- But that's grounds for countdown halt.
- MITCH: We can't take that chance.

774
01:14:27.097 --> 01:14:30.663
Anyone else know a safer way
to buy more time?

775
01:14:33.971 --> 01:14:36.256
Dr. Keller. stretch Watney's rations
four more days.

776
01:14:36.356 --> 01:14:39.515
You're not gonna like it. but that'll get us
to 15. And we'll cancel the inspections.

777
01:14:39.615 --> 01:14:41.664
- Teddy.
- Sir. if that ever got out...

778
01:14:41.764 --> 01:14:46.055
It's on me. You got your two weeks.
Get it done.

779
01:14:46.551 --> 01:14:50.630
WATNEY: So. now I have to hold out
until the probe gets here with more food.

780
01:14:50.730 --> 01:14:54.851
You want to see what minimal calorie
count looks like? Standard issue ration.

781
01:14:54.951 --> 01:14:59.048
But instead of three of these
every one day...

782
01:14:59.148 --> 01:15:03.108
I'm now eating one of these
every three days.

783
01:15:04.453 --> 01:15:07.164
And now. they've asked me...

784
01:15:07.264 --> 01:15:08.315
to do that.

785
01:15:11.343 --> 01:15:13.112
("DON'T LEAVE ME THIS WAY" PLAYING)

786
01:15:13.212 --> 01:15:15.276
The point is...

787
01:15:15.808 --> 01:15:19.328
"stretch the rations four more days..."

788
01:15:19.937 --> 01:15:22.372
(SIGHS) is a real dick-punch.

789
01:15:25.608 --> 01:15:28.907
I'm gonna dip this potato
in some crushed Vicodin.

790
01:15:29.948 --> 01:15:32.217
And there's nobody who can stop me.

791
01:15:42.485 --> 01:15:46.116
It has been seven days
since I ran out of ketchup.

792
01:15:57.584 --> 01:16:00.329
JPL TECHNICIAN 1: Up. Up. up. Yeah.

793
01:16:00.429 --> 01:16:02.456
Let's go up here.

794
01:16:02.556 --> 01:16:04.944
JPL TECHNICIAN 2: Labels facing up.

795
01:16:09.022 --> 01:16:11.892
This is the flight director.
Begin launch status check.

796
01:16:11.992 --> 01:16:14.702
Roger that. Flight.
Beginning launch status check.

797
01:16:14.803 --> 01:16:17.210
Do you believe in God. Vincent?

798
01:16:18.231 --> 01:16:20.026
Yeah.

799
01:16:20.126 --> 01:16:24.313
Yeah. my father was a Hindu.
my mother's a Baptist. so yeah...

800
01:16:24.413 --> 01:16:26.759
I believe in several.

801
01:16:28.734 --> 01:16:30.502
We'll take all the help we can get.

802
01:16:30.602 --> 01:16:32.529
LAUNCH CONTROL TECHNICIAN:
Launch status check complete.

803
01:16:32.629 --> 01:16:35.608
MITCH:
This is Flight. We are go for launch.

804
01:16:35.708 --> 01:16:36.789
TIMER CONTROLLER:
Proceeding with the count.

805
01:16:36.890 --> 01:16:41.175
10. 9. 8. 7. 6...

806
01:16:41.275 --> 01:16:42.878
Main engines start.

807
01:16:42.978 --> 01:16:47.537
4. 3. 2. 1.

808
01:16:48.230 --> 01:16:49.819
Liftoff.

809
01:16:51.826 --> 01:16:53.957
Good thrust.

810
01:16:57.306 --> 01:16:59.532
Performance is nominal.

811
01:17:12.456 --> 01:17:14.523
FEMALE TIMER:
The tail is giving good data.

812
01:17:15.725 --> 01:17:18.879
TIMER CONTROLLER: She's rock solid
at this point. Flight. TVCs look good.

813
01:17:19.179 --> 01:17:21.203
(ALL CHEERING)

814
01:17:30.533 --> 01:17:32.886
We're getting a little shimmy. Flight.

815
01:17:32.986 --> 01:17:34.704
- Say again?
- (BEEP)

816
01:17:34.805 --> 01:17:38.774
- We are getting a very large precession.
- Are we good?

817
01:17:39.409 --> 01:17:40.665
TIMER CONTROLLER:
Flight. it's hitting the redline.

818
01:17:40.765 --> 01:17:44.498
It's spinning on the long axis
around a 17-degree precession.

819
01:17:45.049 --> 01:17:48.702
- Launch. what's happening?
- Force on Iris is 7 G's.

820
01:17:48.803 --> 01:17:51.738
COMMS TECHNICIAN: We've lost
readings on the probe. Flight.

821
01:17:52.139 --> 01:17:54.200
(ALL EXCLAIMING IN DISMAY)

822
01:17:54.400 --> 01:17:57.064
Oh. Jesus Christ.

823
01:18:00.515 --> 01:18:02.890
We've lost it. Flight.

824
01:18:05.762 --> 01:18:06.880
SatCon?

825
01:18:06.980 --> 01:18:09.632
SATCON TECHNICIAN:
No satellite acquisition of signal.

826
01:18:09.732 --> 01:18:11.184
(INDISTINCT MESSAGE)

827
01:18:11.927 --> 01:18:14.538
- TIMER CONTROLLER: L.O.S.
- L.O.S. here. too.

828
01:18:14.638 --> 01:18:18.284
CAPCOM TECHNICIAN: U.S. Destroyer Stockton
reporting debris falling from the sky.

829
01:18:18.384 --> 01:18:20.970
TIMER CONTROLLER: Everyone in the LCC.
maintain your positions...

830
01:18:21.070 --> 01:18:23.435
GC. lock the doors.

831
01:18:52.028 --> 01:18:54.072
WATNEY: "Commander Lewis...

832
01:18:54.172 --> 01:18:58.226
"I may need you to do something for me.

833
01:18:59.127 --> 01:19:01.185
"If I die...

834
01:19:01.285 --> 01:19:04.673
"I need you to check in on my parents.

835
01:19:05.376 --> 01:19:09.240
"They'll wanna hear all about
our time here on Mars.

836
01:19:10.256 --> 01:19:12.283
"I know that sucks.

837
01:19:12.383 --> 01:19:16.412
"And it'll be hard talking
to a couple...

838
01:19:16.512 --> 01:19:18.665
"about their dead son.

839
01:19:19.867 --> 01:19:22.372
"It's a lot to ask.

840
01:19:24.221 --> 01:19:27.299
"Which is why I'm asking you.

841
01:19:27.399 --> 01:19:29.309
"I'm not giving up.

842
01:19:29.409 --> 01:19:34.212
"We just need to prepare
for every outcome.

843
01:19:36.092 --> 01:19:37.833
"Please tell them...

844
01:19:40.138 --> 01:19:42.927
"Tell them I love what I do...

845
01:19:46.419 --> 01:19:48.994
"and I'm really good at it.

846
01:19:50.324 --> 01:19:53.914
"And that I'm dying...

847
01:19:54.678 --> 01:19:57.947
"for something big...

848
01:19:58.782 --> 01:20:00.749
"and beautiful...

849
01:20:04.729 --> 01:20:07.067
"and greater than me.

850
01:20:08.518 --> 01:20:11.894
"Tell them I said I can live with that.

851
01:20:12.463 --> 01:20:14.941
"And tell them...

852
01:20:15.041 --> 01:20:19.104
"thank you for being my mom and dad."

853
01:20:20.889 --> 01:20:24.443
VINCENT: We substituted protein cubes
for the standard rations.

854
01:20:24.543 --> 01:20:28.530
The thrust of the launch combined
with the simultaneous lateral vibration

855
01:20:28.630 --> 01:20:33.185
liquefied the cubes and created
an unbalanced load.

856
01:20:33.285 --> 01:20:36.438
Vincent. why wasn't this addressed
in the inspections phase?

857
01:20:36.538 --> 01:20:40.691
In order to make our launch window.
we were forced to accelerate our schedule.

858
01:20:40.791 --> 01:20:41.563
(BOTH SPEAKING MANDARIN)

859
01:20:41.722 --> 01:20:43.807
Their astronaut is going to die.

860
01:20:45.784 --> 01:20:47.686
Of course there are other ways...

861
01:20:49.255 --> 01:20:52.816
the Taiyang Shen booster.
Our engineers have run the numbers.

862
01:20:52.916 --> 01:20:55.739
and it has enough fuel
for a Mars injection orbit.

863
01:20:56.737 --> 01:20:58.238
Why hasn't NASA approached us?

864
01:20:58.338 --> 01:21:00.015
They don't know.

865
01:21:00.115 --> 01:21:02.734
Our booster technology is classified.

866
01:21:04.962 --> 01:21:08.707
So if we do nothing...

867
01:21:08.807 --> 01:21:13.553
The world would never know
we could have helped.

868
01:21:13.937 --> 01:21:19.125
Then. for the sake of argument.
let's say we decide to help them...

869
01:21:19.343 --> 01:21:23.413
We'd be giving up a booster
and effectively canceling Taiyang Shen.

870
01:21:24.348 --> 01:21:29.536
We need to keep this among scientists.
a co-operation between space agencies.

871
01:21:32.532 --> 01:21:34.297
SANDERS: Yes.

872
01:21:35.051 --> 01:21:37.648
Yes. I understand.

873
01:21:39.831 --> 01:21:41.655
Thank you.

874
01:21:44.829 --> 01:21:47.331
Yes! (SIGHS)

875
01:21:47.431 --> 01:21:51.978
All right. Thanks to my uncle Tommy
in China. we get another chance at this.

876
01:21:52.078 --> 01:21:55.072
Now. we finished
the Iris probe in 62 days.

877
01:21:55.172 --> 01:21:58.508
We are now gonna attempt
to finish it in 28.

878
01:22:09.537 --> 01:22:11.094
(CHIMES)

879
01:22:23.702 --> 01:22:26.612
We can jettison any kind of landing system.
We're only sending rations.

880
01:22:26.712 --> 01:22:29.742
We can... we can crash-land on Mars.

881
01:22:30.443 --> 01:22:32.892
- You should hang up the phone.
- I'm sorry. who are you?

882
01:22:32.992 --> 01:22:37.317
Rich Purnell. I work in Astrodynamics.
and you should hang up the phone right now.

883
01:22:38.685 --> 01:22:42.460
All right. all right.
I'm gonna call you back.

884
01:22:42.873 --> 01:22:45.330
I know how to save Mark Watney.

885
01:22:45.976 --> 01:22:48.513
Your probe plan won't work.
Too many things can go wrong.

886
01:22:48.613 --> 01:22:50.966
- I've got a better way.
- Astrodynamics?

887
01:22:51.066 --> 01:22:52.650
Yeah.

888
01:22:52.750 --> 01:22:55.281
What the hell is "Project Elrond"?

889
01:22:55.581 --> 01:22:58.131
- VINCENT: I had to make something up.
- But "Elrond"?

890
01:22:58.731 --> 01:23:00.716
Because it's a secret meeting.

891
01:23:00.817 --> 01:23:03.494
How do you know that?
Why does "Elrond" mean "secret meeting"?

892
01:23:03.594 --> 01:23:06.223
The Council of Elrond.
It's from Lord of the Rings.

893
01:23:06.546 --> 01:23:09.551
It's the meeting where they decide
to destroy the One Ring.

894
01:23:09.651 --> 01:23:11.578
SANDERS: If we're gonna call
something "Project Elrond"

895
01:23:11.678 --> 01:23:13.998
I would like my code name
to be "Glorfindel."

896
01:23:14.098 --> 01:23:16.050
Okay. I hate every one of you.

897
01:23:16.150 --> 01:23:18.585
What. Teddy doesn't even
know about this yet?

898
01:23:18.685 --> 01:23:22.682
- I'm sorry. who are you?
- VINCENT: This is Rich Purnell. Astrodynamics.

899
01:23:22.782 --> 01:23:24.509
Tell them what you just told me.

900
01:23:24.609 --> 01:23:28.363
I can get the Hermes
back to Mars by Sol 561.

901
01:23:29.464 --> 01:23:31.237
SANDERS: How?

902
01:23:34.677 --> 01:23:37.481
Could you stand
right there for me. please?

903
01:23:38.908 --> 01:23:41.160
Thanks. Right there. Great.

904
01:23:41.260 --> 01:23:45.831
And could you stand right there?
Right there.

905
01:23:49.928 --> 01:23:53.874
Okay. let's pretend
that this stapler is the Hermes

906
01:23:53.974 --> 01:23:56.476
and you are...

907
01:23:56.576 --> 01:24:01.173
- I'm sorry. what's your name again?
- Teddy. I'm the Director of NASA.

908
01:24:01.673 --> 01:24:03.834
Cool. Teddy. you're Earth.

909
01:24:03.934 --> 01:24:06.070
Right now. the Hermes
is headed towards you

910
01:24:06.170 --> 01:24:08.730
starting its month-long deceleration
to intercept.

911
01:24:08.831 --> 01:24:12.641
But instead. what I'm proposing is...
(WHOOSHING)

912
01:24:15.538 --> 01:24:19.475
we start accelerating immediately
to preserve velocity and gain even more.

913
01:24:19.575 --> 01:24:22.162
We don't intercept with Earth at all
but we come close enough

914
01:24:22.262 --> 01:24:24.655
to get a gravity assist
and adjust course.

915
01:24:24.755 --> 01:24:27.334
While we're doing that...

916
01:24:28.803 --> 01:24:31.630
- we resupply with the probe...
- VINCENT: The Taiyang Shen.

917
01:24:31.730 --> 01:24:35.584
...pick up whatever provisions we need
and now we're accelerating towards Mars.

918
01:24:35.684 --> 01:24:36.878
(WHOOSHING)

919
01:24:38.262 --> 01:24:39.671
You're Mars.

920
01:24:39.771 --> 01:24:44.166
Now. we're going too fast at this point
to fall into orbit but... we can do a flyby.

921
01:24:44.266 --> 01:24:47.327
What good is a flyby if we can't
get Watney off the surface?

922
01:24:47.427 --> 01:24:50.505
Watney would intercept using the MAV.

923
01:24:50.605 --> 01:24:52.282
Ow!

924
01:24:52.382 --> 01:24:54.368
(WHOOSHING)

925
01:24:54.818 --> 01:24:57.188
And then we just head home. (WHOOSHING)

926
01:25:01.300 --> 01:25:04.846
I've done the math. It checks out.

927
01:25:05.646 --> 01:25:06.906
- SANDERS: Rich.
- Yes. sir.

928
01:25:07.006 --> 01:25:09.599
- Get out.
- All right.

929
01:25:15.607 --> 01:25:17.284
- Is he right?
- VINCENT: Yeah.

930
01:25:17.584 --> 01:25:20.212
SANDERS: Bruce. what do you think?

931
01:25:20.312 --> 01:25:23.073
Well. if Vincent says so.

932
01:25:23.173 --> 01:25:26.618
- We need to use the Taiyang Shen?
- VINCENT: Uh-huh.

933
01:25:26.718 --> 01:25:29.989
- What am I missing? Why is that important?
- Because we can only do one.

934
01:25:30.089 --> 01:25:32.400
Send Watney enough food
to last till Ares 4

935
01:25:32.500 --> 01:25:34.385
or send Hermes back
to get him right now.

936
01:25:34.485 --> 01:25:38.606
Both plans require the Taiyang Shen.
so we have to choose.

937
01:25:38.706 --> 01:25:41.910
But what about the Hermes crew?
We'd be asking them to add

938
01:25:42.010 --> 01:25:45.013
533 extra days to their mission.

939
01:25:45.113 --> 01:25:47.750
Yeah. They wouldn't hesitate.
not for a second.

940
01:25:47.850 --> 01:25:51.353
Can the Hermes function for 533 days
beyond the scheduled mission end?

941
01:25:51.453 --> 01:25:54.490
It should. Built to last
the full Ares mission

942
01:25:54.591 --> 01:25:57.218
so technically. it's only
halfway through its lifespan.

943
01:25:57.318 --> 01:25:59.929
- But if something goes wrong
- Then we lose the crew.

944
01:26:00.029 --> 01:26:03.150
BRUCE: So what? We either have
a high chance of killing one person

945
01:26:03.250 --> 01:26:06.724
or a low chance of killing six people.

946
01:26:06.824 --> 01:26:08.205
How do we make that decision?

947
01:26:08.505 --> 01:26:11.166
We don't have to make it. Bruce.
He does.

948
01:26:11.366 --> 01:26:15.120
Yeah. well. bullshit.
It should be Commander Lewis' call.

949
01:26:15.220 --> 01:26:18.348
We still have a chance to bring
five astronauts home safe and sound.

950
01:26:18.448 --> 01:26:21.119
I'm not risking their lives.

951
01:26:21.219 --> 01:26:23.705
Let them make that decision.

952
01:26:23.805 --> 01:26:27.570
Mitch. we're going with option one.

953
01:26:28.442 --> 01:26:30.221
You goddamn coward.

954
01:26:48.655 --> 01:26:51.116
- VOGEL: Johanssen?
- Yeah.

955
01:26:51.216 --> 01:26:53.679
I know it's your private time.
Can I bother you for a second?

956
01:26:53.779 --> 01:26:54.921
JOHANSSEN: Yeah. go ahead.

957
01:26:55.021 --> 01:26:57.668
- VOGEL: Where are you?
- The gym.

958
01:27:13.365 --> 01:27:15.279
(BEEPS)

959
01:27:15.877 --> 01:27:17.901
(PANTING)

960
01:27:18.896 --> 01:27:20.948
- What's up?
- I just got an email from my wife

961
01:27:21.048 --> 01:27:24.619
and the subject line says.
"Our children."

962
01:27:24.719 --> 01:27:27.590
My computer won't open the attachment.

963
01:27:28.090 --> 01:27:30.493
Okay. Let's take a look.

964
01:27:34.379 --> 01:27:36.140
Uh...

965
01:27:37.140 --> 01:27:39.101
Let's see.

966
01:27:39.977 --> 01:27:42.336
This isn't a JPEG.

967
01:27:42.781 --> 01:27:46.217
It's a plain ASCII text file.

968
01:27:48.044 --> 01:27:51.147
I don't really know
what we're looking at. It's...

969
01:27:51.947 --> 01:27:54.142
Does that make any sense to you?

970
01:27:54.634 --> 01:27:56.937
"Rich Purnell Maneuver."

971
01:27:57.037 --> 01:28:01.267
It's a... course maneuver
for the Hermes.

972
01:28:05.395 --> 01:28:10.117
And the mission concludes
with Earth intercept. 211 days later.

973
01:28:10.517 --> 01:28:11.911
MARTINEZ: Would it work?

974
01:28:12.011 --> 01:28:14.280
LEWIS: Mmm-hmm. We ran
the numbers. They check out.

975
01:28:14.380 --> 01:28:15.907
BECK: It's a brilliant course.

976
01:28:16.007 --> 01:28:18.770
So why all the cloak and dagger?

977
01:28:18.870 --> 01:28:20.871
Because it goes directly
against NASA's decision.

978
01:28:20.971 --> 01:28:24.950
Yeah. If we do the maneuver. they'd have
to send the supply ship or we die.

979
01:28:25.050 --> 01:28:28.663
We have the opportunity
to force their hand.

980
01:28:29.638 --> 01:28:32.859
So. are we gonna do it?

981
01:28:33.500 --> 01:28:35.402
If it was up to me.
we'd already be on our way.

982
01:28:35.502 --> 01:28:38.064
- But it is. though. isn't it? Up to you.
- (CHUCKLES)

983
01:28:38.164 --> 01:28:42.860
Not this time. This is something
NASA expressly rejected.

984
01:28:43.260 --> 01:28:46.481
We're talking about mutiny here.
which is not a word that I take lightly.

985
01:28:46.581 --> 01:28:49.359
So we do this together or not at all.

986
01:28:49.459 --> 01:28:52.387
And before you answer.
consider the consequences.

987
01:28:52.487 --> 01:28:55.515
If we mess up the supply
rendezvous. we die.

988
01:28:55.716 --> 01:28:58.493
If we mess up the Earth
gravity assist. we die.

989
01:28:58.593 --> 01:29:00.881
If we do everything perfectly

990
01:29:00.981 --> 01:29:04.915
we add 533 days to our mission.

991
01:29:05.368 --> 01:29:09.030
533 more days before we see
our families again.

992
01:29:09.330 --> 01:29:12.413
533 days

993
01:29:12.513 --> 01:29:15.328
of unplanned space travel
where anything could go wrong.

994
01:29:15.528 --> 01:29:18.201
If it's mission critical.

995
01:29:18.301 --> 01:29:20.676
- we die.
- Sign me up.

996
01:29:20.776 --> 01:29:22.494
All right. cowboy. slow down.

997
01:29:22.594 --> 01:29:25.353
You and I. we're military.
Chances are. we go home.

998
01:29:25.453 --> 01:29:27.132
- they'll court martial us.
- Yeah. there's that.

999
01:29:27.232 --> 01:29:31.320
And for the rest of you guys I guarantee
they will never send you back up here again.

1000
01:29:31.420 --> 01:29:36.159
Good. So. if we go for it.
how would it work?

1001
01:29:36.259 --> 01:29:39.287
- I plot the course and execute it.
- JOHANSSEN: Remote override.

1002
01:29:39.387 --> 01:29:42.616
They could take over the Hermes
from Mission Control.

1003
01:29:43.066 --> 01:29:45.001
LEWIS: Can you disable it?

1004
01:29:45.101 --> 01:29:47.320
Hermes has four redundant
flight computers

1005
01:29:47.420 --> 01:29:49.940
each connected to three
redundant comm systems.

1006
01:29:50.040 --> 01:29:52.819
We can't shut down the comms because
we'd lose telemetry and guidance.

1007
01:29:52.919 --> 01:29:56.288
And we can't shut down the computers
because we need to run the ship.

1008
01:29:56.388 --> 01:29:59.651
I'd have to disable
remote override on each system.

1009
01:29:59.751 --> 01:30:01.894
It's part of the OS.
I'd have to jump over the code.

1010
01:30:01.994 --> 01:30:04.536
Okay. but. like. in English.
what would that mean?

1011
01:30:06.733 --> 01:30:08.910
I can do it.

1012
01:30:09.011 --> 01:30:10.841
Great.

1013
01:30:11.604 --> 01:30:13.824
Well. it has to be unanimous.

1014
01:30:13.924 --> 01:30:19.197
If we do this.
it'll be over 900 days of space.

1015
01:30:21.089 --> 01:30:25.036
That's more than enough space
for one life. so...

1016
01:30:25.436 --> 01:30:28.191
- yes.
- I vote yes.

1017
01:30:30.599 --> 01:30:32.998
Let's go get him.

1018
01:30:35.121 --> 01:30:36.915
Johanssen?

1019
01:30:37.015 --> 01:30:39.138
- Yes.
- Yeah!

1020
01:30:39.238 --> 01:30:41.154
(CHEERING. APPLAUDING)

1021
01:30:41.712 --> 01:30:44.339
Got an unscheduled
status update from Hermes.

1022
01:30:44.439 --> 01:30:46.333
- BRENDAN: Roger. Read it out.
- Message reads.

1023
01:30:46.433 --> 01:30:50.212
"Houston. please be advised.
Rich Purnell is a steely-eyed missile man."

1024
01:30:50.312 --> 01:30:51.430
What?

1025
01:30:51.530 --> 01:30:54.560
Flight. Guidance. Hermes is off-course.

1026
01:30:54.660 --> 01:30:58.046
CAPCOM. advise Hermes they're drifting.
Guidance. get a correction ready.

1027
01:30:58.146 --> 01:31:01.145
GUIDANCE TECHNICIAN: Negative. Flight.
it's not drift. They've adjusted course.

1028
01:31:01.245 --> 01:31:05.412
What the hell? Telemetry. any chance
this is instrumentation failure?

1029
01:31:05.512 --> 01:31:06.440
Negative. Flight.

1030
01:31:06.597 --> 01:31:10.125
Guidance. work at how long they can stay
on this course before it's irreversible.

1031
01:31:10.225 --> 01:31:12.394
GUIDANCE TECHNICIAN:
Working on that now. Flight.

1032
01:31:12.494 --> 01:31:15.373
- (WHISPERS) Who's Rich Purnell?
- I don't know.

1033
01:31:15.473 --> 01:31:17.913
Will somebody find out
who the hell Rich Purnell is?

1034
01:31:18.626 --> 01:31:22.254
SANDERS: Annie will go before the media this
morning and inform them of NASA's decision

1035
01:31:22.354 --> 01:31:25.238
to reroute the Hermes to Mars.

1036
01:31:25.474 --> 01:31:28.128
Sounds like a smart move.

1037
01:31:28.228 --> 01:31:30.189
Considering the circumstances.

1038
01:31:30.989 --> 01:31:33.459
Whoever gave them the maneuver...

1039
01:31:33.559 --> 01:31:35.719
only passed along information.

1040
01:31:35.819 --> 01:31:38.221
Crew made the decision on their own.

1041
01:31:39.306 --> 01:31:41.995
You may have killed them. Mitch.

1042
01:31:43.368 --> 01:31:45.071
We're fighting the same war.

1043
01:31:45.171 --> 01:31:48.482
Every time something goes wrong.
the world forgets why we fly.

1044
01:31:48.582 --> 01:31:53.064
I'm trying to keep us airborne.
It's bigger than one person.

1045
01:31:54.288 --> 01:31:56.701
No. It's not.

1046
01:31:58.151 --> 01:32:01.611
When this is over.
I'll expect your resignation.

1047
01:32:05.342 --> 01:32:09.726
- I understand.
- Bring our astronauts home.

1048
01:32:12.299 --> 01:32:14.994
Every Ares mission requires
three years of pre-supplies.

1049
01:32:15.094 --> 01:32:19.124
So NASA decided a long time ago it's a lot
easier to send some of the stuff beforehand

1050
01:32:19.224 --> 01:32:22.310
rather than bring it with us.
So. as a result.

1051
01:32:22.410 --> 01:32:27.515
the MAV for Ares 4 is already there
at the Schiaparelli Crater. just waiting.

1052
01:32:27.615 --> 01:32:31.427
So the plan is for me
to use that to go into orbit

1053
01:32:31.527 --> 01:32:34.573
just as the Hermes is passing...

1054
01:32:34.673 --> 01:32:38.528
and I guess they catch me?

1055
01:32:39.228 --> 01:32:41.426
In space.

1056
01:32:43.091 --> 01:32:46.110
So. I've got 200 sols to figure out

1057
01:32:46.210 --> 01:32:49.047
how to take everything here
that's keeping me alive

1058
01:32:49.147 --> 01:32:52.717
the oxygenator. the water reclaimer.
the atmospheric regulator...

1059
01:32:52.818 --> 01:32:54.770
bring that all with me.

1060
01:32:54.870 --> 01:32:58.691
And luckily. I have the greatest minds
on Planet Earth...

1061
01:32:58.791 --> 01:33:01.810
really. all of the brainpower
on the entire planet

1062
01:33:01.910 --> 01:33:05.448
helping me with this endeavor.
And so far they've come up with.

1063
01:33:05.548 --> 01:33:08.101
"Hey. why don't you drill holes
on the roof of your Rover

1064
01:33:08.201 --> 01:33:11.062
"and hit it as hard as you can
with a rock?"

1065
01:33:11.562 --> 01:33:13.381
We're gonna get there.

1066
01:33:13.481 --> 01:33:15.405
("STARMAN" PLAYING)

1067
01:33:25.761 --> 01:33:26.847
(GROANS)

1068
01:33:28.763 --> 01:33:30.835
(SPEAKING MANDARIN)

1069
01:33:33.935 --> 01:33:38.650
<i>Didn't know what time it was
And the lights were low</i>

1070
01:33:38.750 --> 01:33:42.103
<i>I leaned back on my radio</i>

1071
01:33:42.203 --> 01:33:43.490
(ALL SPEAKING MANDARIN)

1072
01:33:43.590 --> 01:33:46.925
<i>Some cat was layin' down
some rock 'n' roll</i>

1073
01:33:47.025 --> 01:33:49.366
<i>Lotta soul. he said</i>

1074
01:33:51.129 --> 01:33:55.391
<i>Then the loud sound did seem to fade</i>

1075
01:33:55.492 --> 01:34:00.148
<i>Came back like a slow voice
on a wave of phase</i>

1076
01:34:00.248 --> 01:34:05.854
<i>That weren't no DJ
That was hazy cosmic jive</i>

1077
01:34:08.823 --> 01:34:12.911
<i>There's a starman waiting in the...</i>

1078
01:34:13.011 --> 01:34:15.530
533 days longer?

1079
01:34:15.630 --> 01:34:17.540
And you said yes to this?

1080
01:34:17.640 --> 01:34:20.208
He would have done the same for me.
You know that.

1081
01:34:20.308 --> 01:34:21.507
(BOY LAUGHING)

1082
01:34:25.733 --> 01:34:29.415
- Cheese. You do "cheese"? Cheese.
- (CAMERA CLICKS)

1083
01:34:30.604 --> 01:34:33.442
- He didn't do "cheese."
- Did he do "cheese"?

1084
01:34:34.542 --> 01:34:36.050
(GRUNTING)

1085
01:34:41.032 --> 01:34:42.795
- ROBERT: Hey. baby.
- Hey.

1086
01:34:42.895 --> 01:34:45.029
I got something for you.

1087
01:34:45.129 --> 01:34:49.291
Found it in the flea market.
Original pressing.

1088
01:34:49.391 --> 01:34:51.668
LEWIS: No! (EXCLAIMS JOYFULLY)

1089
01:34:51.768 --> 01:34:54.221
- Not a scratch.
- I love it.

1090
01:34:54.321 --> 01:34:57.225
All due respect to your CNSA protocol

1091
01:34:57.325 --> 01:35:01.875
but we haven't done things that way
since Apollo 9.

1092
01:35:01.975 --> 01:35:03.489
(TRANSLATING INTO MANDARIN)

1093
01:35:03.589 --> 01:35:05.876
Did he get that?

1094
01:35:09.878 --> 01:35:14.563
<i>Look out your window.
I can see his light</i>

1095
01:35:14.663 --> 01:35:18.965
<i>If we can sparkle.
he may land tonight...</i>

1096
01:35:19.465 --> 01:35:21.444
TECHNICIAN: Yeah?

1097
01:35:24.045 --> 01:35:25.985
Mmm-hmm.

1098
01:35:27.248 --> 01:35:28.099
Oh!

1099
01:35:28.199 --> 01:35:32.604
<i>There's a starman waiting in the sky</i>

1100
01:35:32.704 --> 01:35:35.174
- (KIDS LAUGHING)
- <i>He'd like to come and meet us</i>

1101
01:35:35.274 --> 01:35:37.476
<i>But he thinks he'd blow our minds</i>

1102
01:35:37.576 --> 01:35:41.013
<i>There's a starman waiting...</i>

1103
01:35:41.113 --> 01:35:43.902
(COUNTING DOWN IN MANDARIN ON PA)

1104
01:35:50.707 --> 01:35:52.917
<i>Let the children use it</i>

1105
01:35:53.017 --> 01:35:55.262
- <i>Let all the children boogie</i>
- (ALL CHEERING)

1106
01:35:55.362 --> 01:35:59.423
<i>There's a starman waiting in the sky</i>

1107
01:35:59.523 --> 01:36:03.896
<i>He'd like to come and meet us
But he thinks he'd blow our minds</i>

1108
01:36:03.996 --> 01:36:08.643
<i>There's a starman waiting in the sky</i>

1109
01:36:09.043 --> 01:36:13.348
<i>He's told us not to blow it
'Cause he knows it's all worthwhile</i>

1110
01:36:13.448 --> 01:36:17.092
<i>He told me. let the children lose it</i>

1111
01:36:17.292 --> 01:36:19.330
<i>Let the children use it</i>

1112
01:36:19.430 --> 01:36:23.218
<i>Let all the children boogie...</i>

1113
01:37:14.804 --> 01:37:16.745
(AIRLOCK HISSING)

1114
01:38:14.743 --> 01:38:17.530
WATNEY: I've been thinking
about laws on Mars.

1115
01:38:17.630 --> 01:38:20.183
There's an international treaty
saying no country can lay claim

1116
01:38:20.283 --> 01:38:21.842
to anything that's not on Earth.

1117
01:38:21.942 --> 01:38:26.930
And by another treaty. if you're not in any
country's territory maritime law applies.

1118
01:38:27.030 --> 01:38:29.927
So Mars is international waters.

1119
01:38:30.827 --> 01:38:35.298
Now. NASA is an American non-military
organization. It owns the Hab.

1120
01:38:35.398 --> 01:38:38.084
But the second I walk outside.
I'm in international waters.

1121
01:38:38.184 --> 01:38:41.304
So here's the cool part. I'm about
to leave for the Schiaparelli Crater

1122
01:38:41.404 --> 01:38:43.447
where I'm gonna commandeer
the Ares 4 lander.

1123
01:38:43.547 --> 01:38:46.244
Nobody explicitly gave me permission
to do this and they can't

1124
01:38:46.344 --> 01:38:48.604
until I'm on board the Ares 4.

1125
01:38:48.704 --> 01:38:52.791
So that means I'm gonna be taking
a craft over in international waters

1126
01:38:52.891 --> 01:38:58.333
without permission. which.
by definition. makes me a pirate.

1127
01:38:58.773 --> 01:39:02.456
Mark Watney. Space Pirate.

1128
01:39:31.949 --> 01:39:34.304
A Space Pirate.

1129
01:40:34.415 --> 01:40:38.143
Everywhere I go. I'm the first.

1130
01:40:39.037 --> 01:40:41.298
It's a strange feeling.

1131
01:40:41.398 --> 01:40:44.992
Step outside the Rover.
first guy to be there.

1132
01:40:45.386 --> 01:40:48.835
Climb that hill. first guy to do that.

1133
01:40:49.573 --> 01:40:53.186
Four and a half billion years...
nobody here.

1134
01:40:53.786 --> 01:40:57.284
And now. me.

1135
01:40:57.883 --> 01:41:01.786
I'm the first person to be alone
on an entire planet.

1136
01:41:12.723 --> 01:41:14.757
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

1137
01:41:16.602 --> 01:41:18.779
How's he doing?

1138
01:41:18.879 --> 01:41:23.727
(CLEARS THROAT) So far. so good.
He's sticking to schedule.

1139
01:41:23.827 --> 01:41:26.846
Drives for four hours before noon...

1140
01:41:26.946 --> 01:41:30.050
lays the solar panels.
waits 13 hours for them to recharge

1141
01:41:30.150 --> 01:41:34.463
and sleeps somewhere in there
and then starts again.

1142
01:41:36.891 --> 01:41:39.926
- How's he doing?
- Uh...

1143
01:41:40.026 --> 01:41:42.725
He asked us to call him
Captain Blondebeard.

1144
01:41:44.825 --> 01:41:49.169
- Technically. Mars would be under maritime...
- Yeah. I know. He explained it to us.

1145
01:41:50.521 --> 01:41:52.698
Where is he?

1146
01:41:52.798 --> 01:41:54.300
- There.
- Okay.

1147
01:41:54.400 --> 01:41:56.566
- Here.
- Okay.

1148
01:43:09.722 --> 01:43:11.782
(BEEPING)

1149
01:43:25.572 --> 01:43:27.600
(BEEPS)

1150
01:43:41.289 --> 01:43:44.880
Okay. we're gonna start by stating for
the record that you're not gonna like this.

1151
01:43:44.980 --> 01:43:47.020
VINCENT: Oh. yeah?

1152
01:43:47.120 --> 01:43:49.673
Yeah. the problem
is the intercept velocity.

1153
01:43:49.773 --> 01:43:52.048
The Hermes. well...

1154
01:43:52.148 --> 01:43:54.496
It can't enter Mars' orbit.

1155
01:43:54.596 --> 01:43:57.874
Otherwise. they'll never have
enough fuel to make it home.

1156
01:43:57.974 --> 01:44:02.646
The MAV. that was only designed
to get to low Mars orbit.

1157
01:44:02.746 --> 01:44:05.190
So in order for Mark to escape

1158
01:44:05.290 --> 01:44:08.167
Mars' gravity entirely
and to intercept the Hermes...

1159
01:44:08.267 --> 01:44:10.120
- He has to be going fast.
- Exactly.

1160
01:44:10.220 --> 01:44:12.632
Which means we need to make
the MAV lighter.

1161
01:44:12.732 --> 01:44:15.400
A lot lighter. 5.000 kilograms lighter.

1162
01:44:15.500 --> 01:44:18.279
- You can do that. right?
- There's some gimmes right off the bat.

1163
01:44:18.379 --> 01:44:22.132
The design presumes 500 kilograms
of Martian soil and samples.

1164
01:44:22.232 --> 01:44:23.668
Obviously we won't do that.

1165
01:44:23.768 --> 01:44:27.506
And there's just one passenger
instead of six.

1166
01:44:27.606 --> 01:44:30.216
With suits and gear. that's another 500?

1167
01:44:30.316 --> 01:44:32.311
Ditch the life support. don't need it.

1168
01:44:32.411 --> 01:44:34.945
And we'll get Mark to wear
his EVA suit the whole trip.

1169
01:44:35.045 --> 01:44:37.590
If he's in his EVA suit.
how is he gonna operate the controls?

1170
01:44:37.690 --> 01:44:39.851
Well. he won't.

1171
01:44:39.951 --> 01:44:43.690
Martinez will pilot the MAV
remotely from the Hermes.

1172
01:44:43.790 --> 01:44:47.477
We've never had a manned ship
controlled remotely before.

1173
01:44:47.977 --> 01:44:48.978
(SIGHS)

1174
01:44:49.078 --> 01:44:52.290
But I am excited about
the opportunities that affords.

1175
01:44:52.390 --> 01:44:55.051
If we go remote. we can lose
the control panels.

1176
01:44:55.151 --> 01:44:57.144
the secondary and tertiary comm systems.

1177
01:44:57.244 --> 01:45:01.912
Wait a second. You want a remote-controlled
ascent with no backup comms?

1178
01:45:04.169 --> 01:45:06.597
He's not even got
to the bad stuff yet. Vincent.

1179
01:45:06.697 --> 01:45:08.165
Well. let's skip to the bad stuff!

1180
01:45:08.565 --> 01:45:13.221
We need to remove the nose airlock.
the windows. and Hull Panel 19.

1181
01:45:14.631 --> 01:45:16.457
You want to take
the front of the ship off?

1182
01:45:16.557 --> 01:45:20.562
Sure. The nose airlock
alone is 400 kilograms.

1183
01:45:20.662 --> 01:45:23.097
You want to send a man into space
without the front of his ship?

1184
01:45:23.197 --> 01:45:24.999
No.

1185
01:45:25.499 --> 01:45:28.503
We're gonna have him
cover it with Hab canvas.

1186
01:45:29.603 --> 01:45:33.092
Look. the hull's mostly there
to keep the air in.

1187
01:45:33.192 --> 01:45:36.370
Mars' atmosphere is so thin.
you don't need a lot of streamlining.

1188
01:45:36.470 --> 01:45:39.907
By the time the ship's going fast enough
for air resistance to matter

1189
01:45:40.007 --> 01:45:42.334
it'll be high enough
that there's practically no air.

1190
01:45:42.434 --> 01:45:45.054
You wanna send him
into space under a tarp.

1191
01:45:45.154 --> 01:45:47.006
Yes.

1192
01:45:47.406 --> 01:45:50.608
- Can I go on?
- No.

1193
01:45:56.691 --> 01:45:59.019
You think he means it like...

1194
01:45:59.319 --> 01:46:01.221
"Are you kidding me?"

1195
01:46:01.321 --> 01:46:02.638
- You know?
- Mmm-hmm.

1196
01:46:02.738 --> 01:46:05.716
Or like. "Are you kidding me?"

1197
01:46:06.643 --> 01:46:09.168
- I think it might be the second one.
- Really?

1198
01:46:09.268 --> 01:46:12.316
- Uh-huh.
- Could be the first way.

1199
01:46:12.416 --> 01:46:16.196
- "Are you kidding me?"
- Yeah. it could be the first way.

1200
01:46:40.454 --> 01:46:42.741
WATNEY: I know what they're doing.

1201
01:46:43.741 --> 01:46:46.452
I know exactly what they're doing.

1202
01:46:46.552 --> 01:46:51.174
They just keep repeating. "Go faster than
any man in the history of space travel."

1203
01:46:51.624 --> 01:46:56.089
Like that's a good thing. Like it'll
distract me from how insane their plan is.

1204
01:46:56.513 --> 01:47:00.250
Yeah. I get to go faster than any man
in the history of space travel...

1205
01:47:00.350 --> 01:47:03.287
because you are launching me
in a convertible.

1206
01:47:03.387 --> 01:47:06.824
Actually it's worse than that because
I won't even be able to control the thing.

1207
01:47:07.024 --> 01:47:09.820
And by the way. physicists.

1208
01:47:09.920 --> 01:47:14.809
when describing things like acceleration
do not use the word "fast."

1209
01:47:14.909 --> 01:47:20.498
So... they're only doing that in the hopes
that I won't raise any objections...

1210
01:47:21.172 --> 01:47:23.049
to this lunacy.

1211
01:47:24.117 --> 01:47:28.829
Because I like the way "fastest man
in the history of space travel" sounds.

1212
01:47:30.357 --> 01:47:32.915
I do like the way it sounds.

1213
01:47:33.602 --> 01:47:36.190
I mean. I like it a lot.

1214
01:47:37.940 --> 01:47:40.370
I'm not gonna tell them that.

1215
01:47:41.753 --> 01:47:43.793
(SIGHS)

1216
01:47:46.016 --> 01:47:47.801
Okay.

1217
01:47:48.601 --> 01:47:50.398
Let's do this.

1218
01:47:50.498 --> 01:47:52.513
("WATERLOO" PLAYING)

1219
01:47:55.993 --> 01:48:02.451
<i>My. my. at Waterloo
Napoleon did surrender</i>

1220
01:48:02.551 --> 01:48:04.219
<i>Oh. yeah</i>

1221
01:48:04.319 --> 01:48:10.742
<i>And I have met my destiny
in quite a similar way</i>

1222
01:48:10.842 --> 01:48:14.071
<i>The history book on the shelf</i>

1223
01:48:14.171 --> 01:48:17.907
<i>Is always repeating itself</i>

1224
01:48:19.376 --> 01:48:24.449
<i>Waterloo. I was defeated.
you won the war</i>

1225
01:48:25.749 --> 01:48:26.926
Come on.

1226
01:48:27.426 --> 01:48:31.271
<i>...promise to love you forevermore</i>

1227
01:48:32.365 --> 01:48:37.487
<i>Waterloo. couldn't escape
if I wanted to...</i>

1228
01:49:37.434 --> 01:49:38.702
(STRAINING)

1229
01:50:21.631 --> 01:50:24.813
LEWIS: Beck. Vogel. I want you guys
in Airlock 2. with the outer door open

1230
01:50:24.913 --> 01:50:26.729
- before the MAV even launches.
- VOGEL: Okay.

1231
01:50:26.829 --> 01:50:30.841
LEWIS: Martinez flies the MAV.
Johanssen sysops the ascent.

1232
01:50:30.941 --> 01:50:34.820
Once we hit intercept.
it's Beck's job to go get Watney.

1233
01:50:34.920 --> 01:50:38.023
- JOHANSSEN: We're ready.
- What's the intercept plan?

1234
01:50:38.123 --> 01:50:42.645
We finished attaching the tethers into
one long line. It's 214 meters long.

1235
01:50:42.745 --> 01:50:45.390
And I'll have the MMU.
so moving around should be easy.

1236
01:50:45.490 --> 01:50:48.509
How fast a relative velocity
can you handle?

1237
01:50:48.609 --> 01:50:50.954
I can grab the MAV
at 5 meters per second.

1238
01:50:51.254 --> 01:50:55.475
10 is like jumping onto a moving train.
So any more than that and I might miss.

1239
01:50:55.575 --> 01:50:57.316
Well. we may have some leeway.

1240
01:50:59.013 --> 01:51:03.979
The launch takes 12 minutes.
And it'll be 52 minutes before intercept.

1241
01:51:04.079 --> 01:51:09.184
Once Mark's engine shuts off. we'll know
our intercept point and velocity.

1242
01:51:09.364 --> 01:51:10.800
Vogel. you're Beck's backup.

1243
01:51:11.100 --> 01:51:13.770
Everything goes well. you pull them
on board with the tether.

1244
01:51:13.870 --> 01:51:16.709
If anything goes wrong.
you go out after him.

1245
01:51:16.809 --> 01:51:20.037
- VOGEL: Yep.
- LEWIS: Okay.

1246
01:51:21.352 --> 01:51:23.415
Let's go get our boy.

1247
01:52:24.962 --> 01:52:28.482
REPORTER: There's a mood of tension and
anxiety here. outside Johnson Space Center.

1248
01:52:28.582 --> 01:52:31.043
As you can see.
many people have gathered here

1249
01:52:31.143 --> 01:52:34.140
to see whether or not the mission
to retrieve Mark Watney

1250
01:52:34.240 --> 01:52:35.957
will be a success.

1251
01:52:36.257 --> 01:52:39.649
Remember. they've had some contact
with him. but it hasn't been very much.

1252
01:52:39.749 --> 01:52:43.290
We have to remind our viewers
that we're watching this as it unfolds.

1253
01:52:43.390 --> 01:52:47.068
So we'll try and keep you up-to-date
as to what exactly is going on.

1254
01:52:47.168 --> 01:52:52.429
Let's listen in to NASA making contact
with Mark Watney. Let's listen in.

1255
01:52:59.173 --> 01:53:01.793
If something goes wrong.
what can Mission Control do?

1256
01:53:01.893 --> 01:53:03.896
Not a damn thing.

1257
01:53:04.496 --> 01:53:07.938
It's all happening 12 light-minutes away
which means it takes 24 minutes

1258
01:53:08.038 --> 01:53:11.069
for them to get the answer
to any question they ask.

1259
01:53:11.369 --> 01:53:13.857
The whole launch is 12 minutes so...

1260
01:53:15.157 --> 01:53:17.592
they're on their own.

1261
01:53:21.538 --> 01:53:23.606
(HISSING IN PAIN)

1262
01:53:34.302 --> 01:53:36.311
(WHIRRING)

1263
01:54:12.093 --> 01:54:14.135
(WOMAN SPEAKING MANDARIN ON PA)

1264
01:54:20.359 --> 01:54:23.663
REPORTER: ...just how long Mark
has been completely alone on Mars.

1265
01:54:23.763 --> 01:54:27.119
We're talking to a psychology
expert later to discuss...

1266
01:54:49.816 --> 01:54:51.868
JOHANSSEN: Fuel pressure. green.

1267
01:54:51.968 --> 01:54:54.143
Engine alignment. perfect.

1268
01:54:54.243 --> 01:54:56.955
Communications. five by five.

1269
01:54:57.056 --> 01:55:00.177
We are ready for pre-flight
checklist. Commander.

1270
01:55:00.627 --> 01:55:04.955
LEWIS: Mission Control. this is Hermes
actual. We will proceed on schedule.

1271
01:55:05.055 --> 01:55:08.485
We are T-minus 2 minutes. 10 seconds
to launch. by the mark.

1272
01:55:09.945 --> 01:55:12.122
About two minutes. Watney.
How you doing down there?

1273
01:55:12.222 --> 01:55:14.174
I'm good.

1274
01:55:14.274 --> 01:55:16.537
I'm anxious to get up to you.

1275
01:55:16.687 --> 01:55:19.067
- Thanks for coming back for me.
- LEWIS: Well. we're on it.

1276
01:55:19.167 --> 01:55:22.671
Remember. you'll be pulling some
serious G's. so it's okay to pass out.

1277
01:55:22.771 --> 01:55:27.478
- You're in Martinez's hands now.
- Well. tell that asshole no barrel rolls.

1278
01:55:27.578 --> 01:55:28.885
(LAUGHS)

1279
01:55:28.985 --> 01:55:30.116
Copy that. MAV.

1280
01:55:30.716 --> 01:55:32.895
- CAPCOM.
- JOHANSSEN: Go.

1281
01:55:32.995 --> 01:55:34.756
- LEWIS: Remote command.
- MARTINEZ: Go.

1282
01:55:34.856 --> 01:55:36.649
- LEWIS: Recovery.
- BECK: Go.

1283
01:55:37.049 --> 01:55:39.611
- LEWIS: Secondary recovery.
- VOGEL: Go.

1284
01:55:39.911 --> 01:55:41.771
Pilot.

1285
01:55:42.271 --> 01:55:43.230
Go.

1286
01:55:43.330 --> 01:55:45.858
- LEWIS: Pilot.
- WATNEY: Go.

1287
01:55:45.958 --> 01:55:48.045
MISSION CONTROL TECHNICIAN:
Copy. We're go.

1288
01:55:48.145 --> 01:55:50.506
LEWIS:
Mission Control. we are go for launch.

1289
01:55:51.289 --> 01:55:53.467
T-minus ten... nine...

1290
01:55:53.567 --> 01:55:56.394
- Main engine start.
- JOHANSSEN: ...eight...

1291
01:55:56.494 --> 01:55:59.289
seven... Mooring clamps released.

1292
01:55:59.389 --> 01:56:02.718
- About five seconds. Watney. Hang on.
- I'll see you in a few. Commander.

1293
01:56:02.818 --> 01:56:04.396
JOHANSSEN: ...four...

1294
01:56:04.696 --> 01:56:06.064
three...

1295
01:56:06.414 --> 01:56:09.024
two... one.

1296
01:56:16.724 --> 01:56:18.778
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1297
01:56:45.305 --> 01:56:49.810
JOHANSSEN: Velocity. 741 meters
per second. Altitude. 1350 meters.

1298
01:56:49.910 --> 01:56:52.372
- That's too low.
- It's fighting me.

1299
01:56:56.258 --> 01:56:58.499
LEWIS: (ECHOING) Watney...

1300
01:56:58.599 --> 01:57:00.861
- do you read?
- (GROANING SOFTLY)

1301
01:57:05.576 --> 01:57:09.923
- MARTINEZ: Booster separation complete.
- Velocity. 850. Altitude. 1843.

1302
01:57:10.023 --> 01:57:12.726
- He's well below target altitude.
- How far below?

1303
01:57:13.326 --> 01:57:14.853
JOHANSSEN: Checking.

1304
01:57:15.053 --> 01:57:16.972
Watney...

1305
01:57:17.072 --> 01:57:19.366
- do you read?
- BECK: He's probably passed out.

1306
01:57:19.466 --> 01:57:21.952
He pulled 12 g's on the ascent.
Give him a few minutes.

1307
01:57:22.052 --> 01:57:23.336
LEWIS: Copy that.

1308
01:57:25.707 --> 01:57:27.701
JOHANSSEN: Main shutdown in three...

1309
01:57:27.801 --> 01:57:31.012
two. one... shutdown.

1310
01:57:32.606 --> 01:57:37.059
MARTINEZ: Back to automatic guidance.
Shutdown confirmed.

1311
01:57:38.920 --> 01:57:41.353
Fuel reserves depleted.

1312
01:57:42.591 --> 01:57:45.498
LEWIS: Watney... do you read?

1313
01:57:46.695 --> 01:57:49.261
It seems there's some sort of problem
with the transmission.

1314
01:57:56.338 --> 01:57:58.019
JOHANSSEN: I have interval pings.

1315
01:57:58.119 --> 01:58:00.085
Intercept velocity will be
11 meters per second.

1316
01:58:00.185 --> 01:58:01.967
I can make that work.

1317
01:58:02.754 --> 01:58:04.956
JOHANSSEN:
Distance at intercept will be...

1318
01:58:05.506 --> 01:58:07.658
we'll be 68 kilometers apart.

1319
01:58:07.758 --> 01:58:12.013
BECK: 68 kilometers?
Did she just say 68 kilometers?

1320
01:58:12.839 --> 01:58:15.552
Come on. guys. keep it together.
Work the problem.

1321
01:58:15.652 --> 01:58:19.807
- Johanssen. time to intercept?
- JOHANSSEN: 39 minutes. 12 seconds.

1322
01:58:20.615 --> 01:58:23.726
Martinez. what if we point our thrusters
in the same direction?

1323
01:58:23.826 --> 01:58:27.405
Well. it depends how much fuel you wanna
save for the altitude adjustments

1324
01:58:27.505 --> 01:58:29.525
- for the trip home.
- How much do you need?

1325
01:58:29.625 --> 01:58:34.472
I can get by with about 20%
of what we have left.

1326
01:58:34.572 --> 01:58:38.325
If we use 75.5% of remaining
altitude-adjust fuel.

1327
01:58:38.425 --> 01:58:40.702
that'll bring the intercept
range to zero.

1328
01:58:40.802 --> 01:58:42.404
Do it.

1329
01:58:42.504 --> 01:58:44.983
Hang on. It brings the range to zero

1330
01:58:45.083 --> 01:58:48.381
but the intercept velocity
will be 42 meters per second.

1331
01:58:48.481 --> 01:58:50.053
And that's way too fast.

1332
01:58:50.663 --> 01:58:54.055
Then we'll have 39 minutes
to figure out how to slow down.

1333
01:58:57.211 --> 01:59:00.492
- Martinez. burn the jets.
- MARTINEZ: Copy that.

1334
01:59:23.048 --> 01:59:26.101
- MAV to Hermes.
- LEWIS: Watney?

1335
01:59:26.201 --> 01:59:28.739
- WATNEY: Affirmative.
- (ALL CHEERING)

1336
01:59:31.231 --> 01:59:35.044
- LEWIS: What's your status?
- WATNEY: My chest hurts.

1337
01:59:35.144 --> 01:59:38.472
I broke my ribs. How are you?

1338
01:59:38.572 --> 01:59:41.308
LEWIS: We're working on getting to you.
There was a complication during launch.

1339
01:59:41.408 --> 01:59:44.721
Copy that. How bad is it?

1340
01:59:44.821 --> 01:59:46.523
LEWIS:
We've corrected the intercept range.

1341
01:59:46.623 --> 01:59:48.450
but we've got a problem
with intercept velocity.

1342
01:59:48.750 --> 01:59:51.545
- WATNEY: How big a problem?
- 42 meters a second.

1343
01:59:52.095 --> 01:59:53.947
Well...

1344
01:59:54.447 --> 01:59:55.709
shit.

1345
02:00:00.763 --> 02:00:04.132
- Commander. I have an idea.
- LEWIS: Go ahead. Mark.

1346
02:00:04.332 --> 02:00:07.446
Well. if I can find
something sharp in here

1347
02:00:07.546 --> 02:00:10.449
and poke a hole in the glove
of my EVA suit

1348
02:00:10.549 --> 02:00:14.661
I could use the escaping air as
a thruster and fly towards you.

1349
02:00:14.761 --> 02:00:17.922
It would be easy to control
because it would be on my arm.

1350
02:00:18.022 --> 02:00:20.008
LEWIS: I can't see you having
any control if you did that.

1351
02:00:20.108 --> 02:00:24.288
You'd be eyeballing the intercept using
a thrust vector you can barely control.

1352
02:00:24.388 --> 02:00:28.142
Yes. Yes. those are all
very good points.

1353
02:00:28.442 --> 02:00:31.861
But... consider this.

1354
02:00:33.297 --> 02:00:35.866
I'd get to fly around like Iron Man.

1355
02:00:35.966 --> 02:00:37.334
(JOHANSSEN LAUGHS)

1356
02:00:37.434 --> 02:00:40.588
WATNEY: Commander... let's go Iron Man.

1357
02:00:43.684 --> 02:00:47.021
- TECHNICIAN 1: This is unexpected LOS.
- TECHNICIAN 2: Communication lost. Stand by.

1358
02:00:48.246 --> 02:00:50.774
Maybe it's not the worst idea.

1359
02:00:50.932 --> 02:00:52.959
No. it is the worst idea.
It's the worst idea ever.

1360
02:00:53.059 --> 02:00:57.667
Not what he said.
Using atmosphere as thrust.

1361
02:00:58.574 --> 02:01:02.509
- What happens if we blow the VAL?
- You want to open the vehicular airlock?

1362
02:01:02.609 --> 02:01:05.382
- It'll give us a good kick.
- But also blow the nose off the ship.

1363
02:01:05.482 --> 02:01:08.726
And all the air would leave
and we need air to not die.

1364
02:01:08.826 --> 02:01:11.237
We would seal the bridge
and the reactor room.

1365
02:01:11.337 --> 02:01:13.406
Everywhere else would go vacuo.

1366
02:01:13.506 --> 02:01:15.576
- Vogel?
- VOGEL: Go ahead. Commander.

1367
02:01:15.976 --> 02:01:18.601
I need you to come inside
and make a bomb.

1368
02:01:18.701 --> 02:01:20.247
Uh... again. Commander?

1369
02:01:20.347 --> 02:01:24.393
LEWIS: You're a chemist. Can you make
a bomb with what you have on board?

1370
02:01:24.943 --> 02:01:26.795
Probably.

1371
02:01:27.404 --> 02:01:30.667
But I feel obliged to mention
that setting off an explosive device

1372
02:01:30.767 --> 02:01:33.528
in a spacecraft
is a terrible. terrible idea.

1373
02:01:33.878 --> 02:01:36.665
Hang on. You guys
making a bomb without me?

1374
02:01:36.765 --> 02:01:39.777
LEWIS: Copy that. Can you do it?

1375
02:01:41.335 --> 02:01:42.350
Ja.

1376
02:01:44.807 --> 02:01:48.418
LEWIS: Houston. be advised.
We're going to deliberately breach the VAL

1377
02:01:48.518 --> 02:01:51.163
- to produce a reverse thrust.
- What?

1378
02:01:51.263 --> 02:01:53.683
Beck. leave your suit on.
Meet Johanssen in Airlock 1.

1379
02:01:53.783 --> 02:01:57.144
We'll open the outer door. I need you
to place the charge on the inner door.

1380
02:01:57.244 --> 02:02:02.201
- Climb back to Airlock 2 along the hull.
- BECK: Copy. I'm on my way.

1381
02:02:08.598 --> 02:02:11.211
- I'm in. Commander.
- LEWIS: Copy that.

1382
02:02:20.486 --> 02:02:23.422
- Vogel. where are you?
- VOGEL: I'm in the kitchen.

1383
02:02:23.522 --> 02:02:25.334
Okay.

1384
02:02:28.494 --> 02:02:31.605
WATNEY: Commander... I can't
let you go through with this.

1385
02:02:31.705 --> 02:02:34.444
- I am prepared to cut the suit.
- Absolutely not.

1386
02:02:34.544 --> 02:02:37.112
WATNEY:
Well. see. the thing is. I'm selfish.

1387
02:02:37.312 --> 02:02:40.178
I want all the memorials
back home to be about me.

1388
02:02:40.278 --> 02:02:43.702
- Just me.
- I should have left this guy on Mars.

1389
02:02:43.952 --> 02:02:45.670
Hey.

1390
02:02:47.873 --> 02:02:50.344
- Sugar?
- Yeah.

1391
02:02:54.130 --> 02:02:55.974
Can you hold this?

1392
02:02:56.074 --> 02:02:57.901
Liquid oxygen...

1393
02:02:58.001 --> 02:03:02.003
and some stain remover
that contains ammonia.

1394
02:03:04.724 --> 02:03:06.725
This thing here...

1395
02:03:06.825 --> 02:03:09.980
is five times stronger
than a stick of dynamite.

1396
02:03:10.080 --> 02:03:11.265
How do we activate it?

1397
02:03:11.365 --> 02:03:13.982
Can you connect this
to one of our lighting panels?

1398
02:03:17.887 --> 02:03:19.415
Careful.

1399
02:03:25.505 --> 02:03:27.852
BECK: Open Airlock 1.

1400
02:03:32.771 --> 02:03:35.224
JOHANSSEN: I'm on the way to Beck.

1401
02:03:38.210 --> 02:03:41.288
- Let's just hope this is a good idea.
- It is.

1402
02:03:41.388 --> 02:03:42.489
JOHANSSEN: Open A1.

1403
02:03:47.737 --> 02:03:49.481
- Hi.
- Hey.

1404
02:03:52.524 --> 02:03:55.033
- You got it?
- Mmm.

1405
02:03:59.850 --> 02:04:02.828
Make sure you're not in here
when this thing goes off.

1406
02:04:04.279 --> 02:04:07.455
Hey. Be careful out there.

1407
02:04:07.555 --> 02:04:09.537
In space.

1408
02:04:12.797 --> 02:04:15.234
Don't tell anyone I did that.

1409
02:04:25.093 --> 02:04:27.381
- Bomb set.
- (BEEPING)

1410
02:04:34.845 --> 02:04:37.863
Leaving Airlock 1.

1411
02:04:42.069 --> 02:04:44.973
MARTINEZ: Guys. I'm running the numbers.
and even with optimal VAL blow

1412
02:04:45.073 --> 02:04:48.536
- we're gonna be off on our angle.
- What's the intercept distance?

1413
02:04:48.636 --> 02:04:51.937
- Johanssen?
- 260 meters. approximate.

1414
02:04:52.037 --> 02:04:53.259
That's too far.

1415
02:04:57.310 --> 02:04:59.406
(GROANS)

1416
02:05:02.449 --> 02:05:06.197
- MARTINEZ: Commander?
- Martinez. close the door.

1417
02:05:08.706 --> 02:05:11.008
Open D3.

1418
02:05:11.108 --> 02:05:12.726
And leave it open.

1419
02:05:40.314 --> 02:05:41.424
(GROANS)

1420
02:05:41.524 --> 02:05:43.633
LEWIS: Open B2.

1421
02:05:47.646 --> 02:05:51.268
Johanssen...
time to VAL blow after initiate?

1422
02:05:51.418 --> 02:05:54.811
- 15 seconds.
- We sure know how to cut it close.

1423
02:05:55.872 --> 02:05:59.526
- Commander?
- Distance is too far. I'm going out.

1424
02:05:59.626 --> 02:06:01.529
- I can do this.
- It's not a debate.

1425
02:06:01.629 --> 02:06:03.612
I'm not risking another crew member.

1426
02:06:03.712 --> 02:06:06.977
Beck's returned.
Johanssen. initiate the bomb.

1427
02:06:07.377 --> 02:06:09.688
- Ten seconds.
- Strap in.

1428
02:06:10.288 --> 02:06:13.533
- JOHANSSEN: Five. four...
- (BEEPING RAPIDLY)

1429
02:06:13.633 --> 02:06:15.927
- three. two...
- Brace for deceleration.

1430
02:06:16.827 --> 02:06:19.594
...one. Activating Panel 41.

1431
02:06:22.701 --> 02:06:24.712
(ALARM BLARING)

1432
02:06:41.163 --> 02:06:43.391
- Bridge seal holding.
- What's the damage?

1433
02:06:43.491 --> 02:06:46.468
LEWIS: Worry about that later.
What's the relative velocity?

1434
02:06:46.568 --> 02:06:50.202
- 12 meters per second.
- LEWIS: Copy.

1435
02:06:52.181 --> 02:06:53.977
Hook me up.

1436
02:06:54.518 --> 02:06:55.640
BECK: Done.

1437
02:07:05.689 --> 02:07:07.260
I have visual on the MAV.

1438
02:07:08.917 --> 02:07:12.380
- What's the intercept range?
- JOHANSSEN: I'm checking.

1439
02:07:12.930 --> 02:07:17.059
- 312 meters.
- Did you say 312?

1440
02:07:17.159 --> 02:07:19.495
Great. I'll wave at you guys as I go by.

1441
02:07:24.681 --> 02:07:26.685
(GROANS)

1442
02:07:28.580 --> 02:07:30.741
I can't get to you. Mark.
You're too far.

1443
02:07:30.841 --> 02:07:32.868
- I'm not gonna make it.
- I know.

1444
02:07:32.968 --> 02:07:34.978
LEWIS:
Beck. unhook me. I'm going after him.

1445
02:07:35.078 --> 02:07:37.490
Commander. I got this.

1446
02:07:51.495 --> 02:07:54.794
- Mark. report.
- WATNEY: On my way. Commander.

1447
02:07:55.299 --> 02:07:57.193
Damn it.

1448
02:07:57.443 --> 02:07:59.247
(GRUNTS)

1449
02:08:06.086 --> 02:08:08.571
Johanssen. what's my relative
velocity to Mark?

1450
02:08:08.671 --> 02:08:12.203
- 5.2 meters per second.
- Copy. Adjusting course.

1451
02:08:18.141 --> 02:08:20.873
JOHANSSEN: 3.1 meters per second.

1452
02:08:22.461 --> 02:08:25.443
Distance to target. 24 meters.

1453
02:08:26.440 --> 02:08:29.237
11 meters to target.

1454
02:08:31.246 --> 02:08:33.019
Six meters.

1455
02:08:42.516 --> 02:08:44.875
(STRAINING) Hold on. Mark.

1456
02:08:57.598 --> 02:08:58.838
(GRUNTING)

1457
02:09:12.814 --> 02:09:15.134
- I got him.
- (PANTING)

1458
02:09:15.234 --> 02:09:16.544
(GASPS)

1459
02:09:16.644 --> 02:09:19.018
- I got him.
- (ALL LAUGHING IN RELIEF)

1460
02:09:19.118 --> 02:09:21.610
- I got him.
- Way to go. Iron Man.

1461
02:09:24.837 --> 02:09:27.421
Beck. pull us in.

1462
02:09:29.207 --> 02:09:30.715
(PANTING) It's good to see you.

1463
02:09:32.644 --> 02:09:34.517
You...

1464
02:09:35.639 --> 02:09:38.734
have terrible taste in music.

1465
02:09:40.778 --> 02:09:42.555
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1466
02:09:48.495 --> 02:09:51.671
JOHANSSEN: Houston.
this is Hermes actual. We got him.

1467
02:09:51.771 --> 02:09:53.226
- (WHOOPS)
- (ALL CHEERING)

1468
02:09:53.326 --> 02:09:55.102
Watney is secure.

1469
02:09:55.202 --> 02:09:56.396
(ALL CHEERING)

1470
02:10:00.415 --> 02:10:02.677
REPORTER 1:
Contact in outer space with Mark Watney.

1471
02:10:02.777 --> 02:10:06.922
After a very long time. they have done
what many people thought was impossible.

1472
02:10:07.022 --> 02:10:10.677
REPORTER 2: Mission confirmation:
Mark Watney has been successfully rescued.

1473
02:10:10.777 --> 02:10:12.506
(FEMALE REPORTER SPEAKING MANDARIN)

1474
02:10:14.665 --> 02:10:17.145
LEWIS: Grab a hold of him.

1475
02:10:18.451 --> 02:10:21.865
- Hey. handsome!
- Beck. close the hatch.

1476
02:10:24.475 --> 02:10:25.759
Hey. guys!

1477
02:10:30.198 --> 02:10:34.422
LEWIS: Houston. six crew safely aboard.

1478
02:10:37.121 --> 02:10:39.358
This is huge moment for this nation.

1479
02:10:39.458 --> 02:10:43.397
for the world and indeed.
for international space travel.

1480
02:10:43.796 --> 02:10:46.234
LEWIS:
I can't believe anything you do works.

1481
02:10:46.564 --> 02:10:48.424
Hey!

1482
02:10:49.860 --> 02:10:52.482
- Oh. God.
- JOHANSSEN: I can't believe it.

1483
02:10:53.306 --> 02:10:55.198
There's a little smell
going on over there. bud.

1484
02:10:55.298 --> 02:10:59.095
I know. I haven't had a shower
in a year and a half.

1485
02:10:59.195 --> 02:11:02.372
Don't make me laugh. I have broken ribs.

1486
02:11:35.700 --> 02:11:37.572
Hey. there.

1487
02:11:45.344 --> 02:11:47.446
- Morning. sir.
- It's an honor. sir.

1488
02:11:47.546 --> 02:11:50.767
- Sir.
- Sir.

1489
02:11:51.217 --> 02:11:53.235
MALE CADET: Morning. sir.

1490
02:12:06.316 --> 02:12:08.333
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

1491
02:12:14.257 --> 02:12:17.019
WATNEY: Welcome to the Astronaut
Candidate Program.

1492
02:12:17.119 --> 02:12:21.032
Now pay attention.
because this could save your life.

1493
02:12:21.132 --> 02:12:23.777
- Trust me. I know what I'm talking about.
- (ALL LAUGH)

1494
02:12:23.877 --> 02:12:27.462
All right. let me get a few things
out of the way. right off the bat. Yes...

1495
02:12:27.565 --> 02:12:32.644
I did in fact survive on a deserted
planet by farming in my own shit.

1496
02:12:33.144 --> 02:12:37.242
Yes. it's actually worse than it sounds.
So let's not talk about that ever again.

1497
02:12:38.684 --> 02:12:41.821
The other question I get
most frequently is...

1498
02:12:41.921 --> 02:12:44.432
"When I was up there.
stranded by myself...

1499
02:12:44.532 --> 02:12:47.259
"did I think I was going to die?"

1500
02:12:47.609 --> 02:12:50.088
Yes. absolutely.

1501
02:12:50.188 --> 02:12:53.150
And that's what you need to know going in
because it's going to happen to you.

1502
02:12:53.550 --> 02:12:57.195
This is space. It does not cooperate.

1503
02:12:57.295 --> 02:13:00.065
At some point. everything
is going to go south on you.

1504
02:13:00.165 --> 02:13:03.234
Everything is going to go south
and you're going to say. "This is it.

1505
02:13:03.334 --> 02:13:05.763
"This is how I end."

1506
02:13:06.363 --> 02:13:10.533
Now. you can either accept that
or you can get to work.

1507
02:13:11.435 --> 02:13:13.190
That's all it is.

1508
02:13:13.290 --> 02:13:15.965
You just begin.

1509
02:13:16.065 --> 02:13:19.110
You do the math.
You solve one problem...

1510
02:13:19.210 --> 02:13:21.672
then you solve the next one.
And then the next.

1511
02:13:21.772 --> 02:13:24.775
And if you solve enough problems.
you get to come home.

1512
02:13:25.518 --> 02:13:28.337
All right. questions?

1513
02:13:28.862 --> 02:13:30.935
("LOVE TRAIN" PLAYING)

1514
02:13:32.700 --> 02:13:35.293
ANNIE: Once Mission Control
completes their pre-flight checks

1515
02:13:35.393 --> 02:13:37.471
we'll begin launch procedures.

1516
02:13:37.571 --> 02:13:40.133
The Ares 5 team will rendezvous
with the Hermes

1517
02:13:40.233 --> 02:13:43.344
approximately 48 minutes after launch.

1518
02:13:43.444 --> 02:13:47.140
From there. they will have 414 days
of space travel ahead of them.

1519
02:13:47.240 --> 02:13:51.320
REPORTER: Have the goals changed from
the previous mission to the Ares 5 program?

1520
02:13:51.420 --> 02:13:53.513
And what do you hope to achieve
this time around?

1521
02:13:53.613 --> 02:13:57.935
VINCENT: Well. no. The goals have always
been the same for the Ares program.

1522
02:13:58.035 --> 02:14:00.755
This time. of course. we hope to bring
all the astronauts back at the same time.

1523
02:14:00.855 --> 02:14:01.789
(REPORTERS LAUGHING)

1524
02:14:01.889 --> 02:14:05.225
- Flight. Guidance check complete.
- BRENDAN: Copy. Guidance.

1525
02:14:05.325 --> 02:14:09.096
This is Flight. We are go
for launch. on schedule.

1526
02:14:09.196 --> 02:14:11.212
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

1527
02:14:19.475 --> 02:14:21.993
REPORTER ON TV: Final aerosurface
checks are complete.

1528
02:14:22.093 --> 02:14:25.681
as everything remains a go
for the launch of the Ares 5.

1529
02:14:25.781 --> 02:14:27.854
20 seconds.

1530
02:14:28.301 --> 02:14:30.244
MISSION CONTROL TECHNICIAN:
Proceeding with the count.

1531
02:14:30.344 --> 02:14:33.990
T-minus 10. 9... Main engine start.

1532
02:14:34.090 --> 02:14:38.052
7. 6. 5. 4...

1533
02:14:38.152 --> 02:14:41.608
3. 2. 1.

1534
02:14:41.708 --> 02:14:43.010
MALE REPORTER: And liftoff.

1535
02:14:43.110 --> 02:14:46.527
As the crew of the Ares 5
begin the next chapter

1536
02:14:46.627 --> 02:14:49.138
of American space exploration.

1537
02:14:49.238 --> 02:14:50.891
MISSION CONTROL TECHNICIAN:
Pressures look good.

1538
02:14:50.991 --> 02:14:53.956
- (ALL CHEERING)
- (WHOOPS)

1539
02:15:03.462 --> 02:15:05.471
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

1540
02:15:09.302 --> 02:15:10.760
Wow. Good shot.

1541
02:15:10.860 --> 02:15:14.741
REPORTER ON TV: There you have it. Five years
after the rescue of astronaut Mark Watney

1542
02:15:14.841 --> 02:15:18.249
an Ares 5 is on its way to Mars.

1543
02:16:04.564 --> 02:16:06.611
("I WILL SURVIVE" PLAYING)

